INSERT INTO `comment` VALUES (2,'dowser','2021-08-16 02:59:00','Those in comfortable situations have a great difficulty grokking other realities.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321819'),(2,'GL2814','2021-08-16 01:28:00','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0BVRhsqHE5M\n(ED. NOTE: In 2015, Edge presented \"A Short Course in Superforecasting\" with political and social scientist Philip Tetlock. Superforecasting is back in the news this week thanks to the UK news coverage of comments by Boris Johnson\'s chief adviser Dominic Cummings, who urged journalists to \"read Philip Tetlock\'s Superforecasters [sic], instead of political pundits who don\'t know what they\'re talking about.\")\nhttps://www.edge.org/event/a-short-course-in-superforecasting%E2%80%94philip-tetlock-an-edge-master-class\nhttps://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02684527.2016.1147164\nhttps://science.sciencemag.org/content/355/6324/481.abstract','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321792'),(2,'cdob63','2021-08-15 19:25:00','As a general historic principle, the embassy is sort of an abstract idea.  If the US designates the airport as the site where its ambassador is or will be conducting the diplomatic business of the United States, the \"embassy\" is probably the ambassador\'s chair in the airport lounge.  Once the ambassador and all the diplomatic staff have left the country or have stopped conducting business, there is no embassy.  Should be pretty much any minute now.  \nIf I were the GJedi (which as you have probably guessed I am not), I would go with the usual understanding of the term, and declare the embassy evacuated when no diplomatic business is being conducted in the buildings in town even if the ambassador is still signing things out at the airport.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321684'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-15 19:28:00','Yes, but in modern parlance, an embassy is considered the sovereign territory of the country represented by the embassy. You can\'t really make that claim about an airport lounge.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321688'),(2,'cdob63','2021-08-15 19:50:00','Yeah, you can.  You are of course perfectly correct that the GJedi should shut this Q down under the normal-people understanding of the term as soon as the buildings are emptied of State Department functionaries. But as with the jargon in many fields of endeavour, there is both a technical and a common-sense meaning of the term, which nobody except specialists cares about, nor should they.\nIn essence:  If that\'s where the US government says the duly accredited ambassador is conducting the business of the United States, then that chair is US territory.  In this case, that would only mean that the person of the ambassador can\'t be interfered with, which is essentially the historic sense of the whole thing.  Once the ambassador leaves, if there\'s an officially designated charge d\'affaires, then the embassy is wherever that person is doing business.  Once there is no designated successor and no diplomatic business is being conducted, or once either government declares the mission defunct, then there is no embassy any more.  \nHave to sign off now; I am falling behind in my nit-picking. . . .','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321697'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-15 19:58:00','Thanks; looks like I was wrong. In any case the question will close as a \"yes\" shortly, if it hasn\'t already.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321699'),(2,'cdob63','2021-08-15 20:11:00','Yeah.  And your common sense wasn\'t wrong, @rjfmgy, which is what really matters.   Good thing the GJedi are not as much of a pain in the proverbial as I am.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321700'),(2,'ctsats','2021-08-15 20:29:00','I have submitted a clarification request, as follows:\n\"I take it that the spirit of the question is about the diplomatic presence of US in Kabul, and not the building of the embassy itself. Under such an interpretation, evacuation of the embassy itself while US diplomatic personnel is still present in the city airport is not enough to resolve the question positively.\nKindly clarify if such an interpretation is in accordance to the spirit of the question or not.\"\ncc @cdob63','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321709'),(2,'cdob63','2021-08-15 20:46:00','Probably worth a try, @ctsats, but the situation will probably be clear in either sense before they get around to answering.  I imagine the intent of the question was about the buildings, but it never hurts to ask.  \nOriginally, \"mission\" and \"embassy\" referred to the functions of the ambassador and staff, and only later attached to the land and structures, when the missions permanently acquired those bits.  The diplomatic immunity of the ambassador and staff then were extrapolated to the buildings and grounds, which is roughly how we got to the present state of affairs.  This will not be on the exam.   Thanks.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321715'),(2,'cdob63','2021-08-15 21:13:00','Just spotted this in a BBC story ( https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-asia-58219963/page/2 ):\nUS Secretary of State Anthony Blinken says the US is moving its embassy compound to Kabul airport.\nHe told ABC News: \"It\'s why we had forces on hand - to make sure we could do this in a safe and orderly fashion. The compound itself, folks are leaving there and going to the airport.\"\nSo he\'s sticking to the traditional usage.  Not sure when the accredited ambassador left town; last person out of the compound in town was apparently the charge d\'affaires, who has \"relocated\" to the airport.  So perhaps the GJedi will adhere to the original usage.  Won\'t matter in a few hours anyway, I don\'t suppose.  \nI am a bit surprised that the Taliban didn\'t wait until 01 September, when the US said they would be gone.  Perhaps they had factions inside the group that wouldn\'t hold back.  Anyway, they seem to be more or less behaving themselves at the moment.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321726'),(2,'ctsats','2021-08-15 21:59:00','Thanks, had seen this already, but not sure it clarifies the issue.\n>  Won\'t matter in a few hours anyway\nIMO, I am not sure that, at the end of the day, they will certainly choose to leave Kabul; as you correctly say, the Taliban seem to behave themselves so far, and there don\'t seem to be any reports for hostile actions against the Americans. But it is indeed a highly uncertain situation.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321754'),(2,'cdob63','2021-08-16 00:00:00','You\'re right, @ctsats.  I think it rather muddies it further.  The language in the Q sounds like they\'re talking about buildings, but the official jargon says the embassy is now in the airport.  This sort of confusion goes on all the time in other areas:  Is \"the church\" our building or our congregation?  Is \"the company\" our offices or our workers, especially when there are none of them in the offices?  You can presumably \"lose control\" of a congregation or a staff, but having to \"evacuate\" them is not an appetizing prospect.  \nThe Q does specify \"in Kabul,\" although that probably wasn\'t deliberate.  So if they gather someplace else--even if the Kabul airport is technically in another burg, as many airports are--it is a Yes.  One feels sorry for those who thought they were asking a simple question--I don\'t suppose anybody foresaw this unseemly heap of possibilities.\n    \n    Show more','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321781'),(2,'ctsats','2021-08-15 14:38:00','I have asked for a clarification; does the question mean the embassy building itself, or the presence of US diplomatic personnel in Kabul? If it is the latter , it has certainly not happened, at least not yet, i.e. the embassy has effectively be moved to the airport.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321565'),(2,'Paver','2021-08-16 09:48:00','This is a really good point. I\'m still currently seeing reports of embassy personnel at Kabul airport, though it\'s unclear to me A) if they are still operating in any functional capacity or B) if they will still be in-country in a few days time. I suspect the answer to both is \"no\", but that\'s a different question, I suppose.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321872'),(2,'lsgold7','2021-08-15 15:38:00','That seems to qualify as evacuating embassy.\nI took it to mean US would abandon physical embassy for 2d time and a skeleton crew  is at airport on way out.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321602'),(2,'Terry-Smith','2021-08-15 19:31:00','@isgold7 Yeah this one’s done, glad to see you put in your 100%.\nBtw I just went back and reread all the forecasts people made, excluding the ones without rationales. So many forecasting lessons here with this question. I got it wrong early on, but the main thing is to learn from it','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321692'),(2,'lsgold7','2021-08-15 19:49:00','Yes I bought into the Potemkin village narrative too completely\n@dowser  right on target. \nI heard Retired Adm. Mullen....\nWhy did they withdraw at peak of fighting season.\nCould have gotten more people out \nThat leaves a really bad taste in my mouth \nOne thing to retreat this was a retreat with dishonor','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321695'),(2,'Wildwood2000','2021-08-16 02:18:00','Hi Gl, I should be back soon, still having a bit of trouble with blood clots. Mostly to pull my own research for the doctors> LOL','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321808'),(2,'GL2814','2021-08-16 03:08:00','I wish you well companero https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Qo3F-0keq8','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1321820'),(2,'lsgold7','2021-08-13 20:37:00','Me too.\nYou reacted to events quickly.\nI thought there were battles for Herat Kandahar and Lashgar Gah and Herat.\nThere were.\nGovt. lost every battle.\nWas this because the regime was corrupt and inefficient, or was it because obviously Pakistan formed a Taliban army capable of tactical and strategic maneuver.\nProbably both \nIt took a lot of supplies and coordination from Pakistan.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320861'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-13 20:46:00','The U.S. has a perverse habit of trying to create duplicates of the U.S. armed forces in places where the social and political circumstances and have developed in ways that do not lend themselves to grafted-on American style institutions.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320867'),(2,'dowser','2021-08-14 02:47:00','Those that know how to use hammers (on everything is a nail) get promoted.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320980'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-13 15:29:00','I wouldn\'t worry about the U.S. government remaining silent if the embassy is abandoned. You can bet there will be press coverage of the Taliban rampaging through it, firing guns in the air, etc. if the embassy is evacuated. We\'ll find out, official announcement or not.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320694'),(2,'probahilliby','2021-08-13 14:49:00','@Anneinak  Oh how I wish we could score them probabilistically.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320682'),(2,'Anneinak','2021-08-13 19:48:00','@probahilliby, \nI\'m feeling a bit embarrassed to admit this, but I don\'t understand what you mean.  Why isn\'t 98% a probabilistic score?\nThanks!','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320845'),(2,'probahilliby','2021-08-13 21:49:00','I\'m sorry for the confusion @Anneinak. I meant to say that I wish we could score the CIA / US intelligence agency on the Afghanistan crisis.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320880'),(2,'jflom','2021-08-14 00:25:00','lol now that\'s a great comment','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320929'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-13 08:03:00','Here\'s a hypothetical: What does the U.S. do if regime forces do resist in Kabul, and at least temporarily blunt the Taliban push to take the capital? Does the U.S. do nothing, so as not to antagonize the Taliban, which already controls much of the country, and by the time they get to Kabul, will probably win the war? Or does it assist the Kabul regime with ammunition, supplies, maybe air support, in order to maintain its credibility and not abandon an ally? In the latter case, of course, it will antagonize the Taliban, and make the worst case all the more likely. If you can\'t answer, I know how you feel; I don\'t know the answer either. Nobody in Washington can answer that question, and nobody in Washington wants to have to. But I do know both options are bad, and so does everybody else.\nThe U.S. embassy in Kabul is not like just any embassy in any country. It is the proconsular headquarters of the foreign power that has installed the current regime and has kept it alive for twenty years. And in doing so, it has kept the Taliban from achieving power (or more accurately, regaining power) in Afghanistan. So the U.S. can make all the  noises it wants asking, begging, or demanding that the Taliban leave the embassy alone. And the predictable response of the Taliban will be, \"Why should we?\" The U.S. can\'t wage war for two decades and then, when it is giving up, expect that its erstwhile enemy will cut it a break. The world, warfare, and international relations just don\'t work that way. The United States is not neutral in this war, it never has been, and it can\'t plead that it is now just a bystander. To the Taliban, the United States is the enemy. In my opinion, once Washington abandons its fantasy that it can negotiate its way out of this mess, it will become obvious that it must evacuate the embassy.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320546'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-13 04:14:00','Good link. Here\'s one:\nhttps://republicans-armedservices.house.gov/news/press-releases/rogers-we-are-watching-president-biden-s-saigon-moment-unfold-us\nA good example of America\'s political class, many of whose members show no capacity to understand that sometimes there are no good choices.\n@aaseawaf15\'s observation above is probably right, and we will see a cascade of ever-increasing violence before this ends; but maybe it will end quickly. Whatever the case, U.S. intervention at this stage will only drag it out, and it is absolutely loathsome to use this debacle as a stick to beat the administration with, and Rep. Rogers does with his statement.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320480'),(2,'lsgold7','2021-08-13 01:57:00','I agree. Recognition of the regime in power is necessary. Eventually we reopened relations with Vietnam.\nAll US does is refuse a seat at the table.\nWe may find the Taliban a blood thirsty regime and their values abhorrent making it even more important to engage.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320443'),(2,'dowser','2021-08-13 02:47:00','Those who ignore history are doomed to repeat the bad parts. US woefully lacking in some of the basic education things that might keep the cockroaches from being the only survivors.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320458'),(2,'lsgold7','2021-08-13 02:55:00','So true. Vietnam redux.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320463'),(2,'aaseawaf15','2021-08-13 04:06:00','@lsgold7 @dowser @rjfmgy \nWhatever the outcome in the coming months, it will be bloody. \nFrance 24, 08/08/21, \'On the frontline: Afghan woman governor recruits anti-Taliban militia\': https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20210806-on-the-frontline-afghan-woman-governor-recruits-anti-taliban-militia','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320476'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-12 23:18:00','Biden will take heat no matter what happens. Surely some people will ask, \"Who lost Afghanistan?\" But this question is fatuous because we never had Afghanistan to begin with. And everybody knows this. Harping on the \"loss\" of Afghanistan will score no points with anyone who insists upon engaging in it.\nBut the one question nobody in Washington wants to have to answer is, \"Why didn\'t you evacuate the embassy when there was still time?\" It is the uncertainty that makes the evacuation essentially inevitable. The best outcome is that the embassy remains and is unmolested. But the United States has absolutely