er present in the embassy at all times?\" Another is, \"Will decreasing the number of staff be a strategy for the US to deter insurgents from trying to kidnap or hold hostage embassy members?\"\nHistorically, attacks on the embassy have not resulted in full evacuations and lockdowns are more often the response. What makes this case different? Why must the response be different or the same?\nFurther, the Taliban failed today to overtake Mazar-e-Sharif on its first go and was reportedly met with strong opposition. Mazar-e-Sharif is 10x smaller than Kabul population wise but one of the biggest cities in the country, so what are the chances Taliban take over Kabul if conquering Mazar-e Sharif remains a struggle. Also, people are fleeing to Kabul, which should give an implied sense of security there compared to other places in Afghanistan.\nBecause I do not know much to adequately answer such questions, I cannot support a high probability of this event happening—personally.\nBut we can\'t confidently say no either, can we?\n@Terry-Smith @Jean-luc-Nadeau @dowser @DNK89 @ndeyoung','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1319972'),(2,'dowser','2021-08-12 05:23:00','I agree probably SecState, but after consulting POTUS, and lining up the \"who lost AF\" narrative.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1319977'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-12 05:38:00','\"known stances of either of these individuals\"\nNo idea. But I take note of the fact that Biden in his first few months in office announced his intention to withdraw from Afghanistan. \n\"Is there a U.S. interest in having at least one member present in the embassy at all times?\" \nNone that I can see.\n\"Will decreasing the number of staff be a strategy for the US to deter insurgents from trying to kidnap or hold hostage embassy members?\"\nNo, but taking them all out guarantees no crisis at all involving the embassy (such crises perhaps taking more than one form, including some that neither of us has thought of).\n\"Historically, attacks on the embassy have not resulted in full evacuations and lockdowns are more often the response. What makes this case different? Why must the response be different or the same?\"\nI don\'t know which other attacks you\'re referring to. As far as \"the same\" vs. \"different\" goes, we have no idea what is going to happen. We know what *might* happen, and what the worst case scenario might be (Tehran and Benghazi are examples). So the question is, given that the U.S. has been the enemy of the Taliban for twenty years, is is prudent and realistic to expect a less-than-worst-case scenario? Note that I am not saying that the worst case scenario would definitely come to pass if the embassy staff remained in place; I merely believe that it is neither prudent nor realistic to think so. You seem to disagree. You may be right, but my opinion is that the administration should not take the chance of finding out. If the Taliban actually do want international respectability, and exercise the degree of control that guarantees the safety of the embassy, it can always reopen. \n\"Further, the Taliban failed today to overtake Mazar-e-Sharif on its first go and was reportedly met with strong opposition. Mazar-e-Sharif is 10x smaller than Kabul population wise so what are the chances that they may take over Kabul if Mazar-e Sharif remains a struggle.\"\nPerhaps so; here\'s question for you: How many Taliban troops are deserting and/or turning their weapons over to regime troops? Here\'s another question: How many Afghan warlords who now support the regime are simply holding out for the best deal they can get from the Taliban? And this one: How long can the regime troops hold out in isolated cities with no logistical support? I\'m not saying they can\'t do it, but I am saying they can\'t do it forever.\nWhatever the case, the more success the Taliban has, the more it will have. That is, the more it looks like the Taliban will win, the less its opponents will be willing to resist.\n\"...people are fleeing to Kabul, which should give an implied sense of security there compared to other places in Afghanistan.\"\nIndeed it does imply that. So what? The Taliban aren\'t operating in the vicinity of Kabul yet. That doesn\'t mean they never will. Six months ago, they weren\'t operating in a lot of places that they control now.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1319979'),(2,'DNK89','2021-08-12 06:51:00','There is this\nhttps://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/8/11/afghan-capital-could-fall-to-taliban-within-90-days-us-intel','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320002'),(2,'probahilliby','2021-08-12 08:46:00','@rjfmgy - I know nothing to answer your questions without ignorant speculation, sorry. I would like to say though that I\'m not necessarily disagreeing to your points.\n- There have been previous insurgent attacks on the embassy that included machine guns, suicide vests, RPGs, etc.\n- At my lowest forecast, I was at 16% yes while the crowd was around 9% yes. This means initially I saw these events coming probabilistically relative to the crowd, but I am arguing that even though the evidence presented as of late point strongly to a YES resolution, it does not mean that it is likely. For example, if evidence fits 90% to an extremely rare event, perhaps the probability is now 1%—still not likely to happen (see Bayesian inference). There are still things that can be argued for NO resolution. One that is pending is whether or not the government, media, and/or eyewitnesses would need to confirm this.\n- Also, the US intelligence community report says it could occur. Could is ambiguous. Could could mean 10% or 50%, two different forecasts.\n- With such a crisis, there is a stronger need for embassies to help stranded citizens. On the other hand, the US Embassy\'s warning to leave the country could mean a looming evacuation pertinent to this question.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320036'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-08-12 15:47:00','The embassy\'s warning to U.S. citizens also made the point that the embassy may ultimately not be able to help them, so the should get out now.\n\"There have been previous insurgent attacks on the embassy that included machine guns, suicide vests, RPGs, etc.\" It seems to me that comparing hit-and-run attacks on the embassy when the U.S.-supported regime is in control of the capital to the possibility of a crisis in a Taliban-controlled capital is comparing the apples and oranges. So I didn\'t take those attacks into consideration because I consider them to be irrelevant to the question at hand.\n\"For example, if evidence fits 90% to an extremely rare event, perhaps the probability is now 1%—still not likely to happen (see Bayesian inference). \" I don\'t consider Taliban control of Afghanistan to be \"an extremely rare event;\" I consider the U.S.-supported regime to be the anomaly. The regime was installed by the U.S.; the Taliban won power on its own in the 1990s. Thus, I don\'t consider a total Taliban victory improbable.\nHere\'s what I see as the difference between your approach and mine: in my view, the administration is not going to view this as a statistical problem and formulate its policy based on a calculation of probabilities. It is going to formulate its policy by deciding what makes it look least bad, and provides the least painful solution for the administration. That is, they don\'t want a hostage crisis, they don\'t want to have to shoot their way into and out of Kabul, they don\'t want to have to fly helicopters or tiltrotor aircraft over hostile territory and possibly have to land them under fire (and lose some of them), and they don\'t want to bet all their chips on the beneficence of the Taliban.\nThey don\'t want a replay of Tehran, Saigon, Mogadishu or Benghazi. In my opinion, the odds of any of these actually happening are irrelevant. The relevant factor is, that if any of them - alone or in combination - *do* happen, the administration is going to look terrible, and the probability that the administration is sanguine about looking terrible is 0%.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320150'),(2,'dowser','2021-08-11 23:47:00','Did you mean 0%?','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1319882'),(2,'Terry-Smith','2021-08-12 00:14:00','No, I meant 70%. There’s no way to delete it unfortunately','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1319888'),(2,'probahilliby','2021-08-13 14:54:00','@cjmattco  I think I was wrong here. The US doesn\'t need an attack to evacuate. All evidence points that they are proactively trying to prevent something bad happening to the staff. Attack or not, they seem to be preparing to evacuate most if not all staff. My thinking is that they are preparing the embassy building now (destroying sensitive documents) and then will proceed to evacuate those who are not needed and relocate the remaining essential members to an undisclosed location, perhaps the Kabul international airport where it is more fortified with international militia. It also serves as a quick escape from the country if needed.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320686'),(2,'cjmattco','2021-08-13 15:41:00','@probahilliby, I’ve revised my forecast upwards. What a week!','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1320697'),(2,'dowser','2021-08-11 03:22:00','I\'d count on it and the window of \"easy\" opportunity may be closing.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1319538'),(2,'Jean-luc-Nadeau','2021-08-11 02:41:00','Intervention by air is no more accurate and nuclear is unthinkable. On the field, i should say, on the mountain talibans are, for now the only player. If the strategy is to win over all cities,  i cannot see why they would stop for Kabul. I see it more like a Teheran scenario, than a Baghdad one.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1319530'),(2,'erikbays','2021-08-09 05:23:00','Mapping Taliban control\nhttps://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-57933979','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1318666'),(2,'erikbays','2021-08-09 16:54:00','Taliban takes sixth provincial capital\nhttps:/