,'https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1309516'),(2,'cdob63','2021-07-19 14:17:00','Good points all around, @rjfmgy and @dowser.  My suspicion, which may be too strong a term, is that outfits like the Taliban don\'t move into the big cities in force until they\'ve consolidated their wins in the countryside.  Think Cuba, for example, or Vietnam, or the seditionist traitors (now courageous patriots) in the American Revolution.   It\'s easier for insurgents to hold small towns than big cities, and the local troops and any interested outside parties are less likely to bother trying to clear the countryside; it\'s harder to hold and stretches your forces thinner.  So except for the odd show raid and missile attack, the Taliban will tend to stay out of town for a while yet--however tight an organization it is (and thanks for raising that issue, which I had neglected).   \nI don\'t think they have to abandon an assault on the embassy to be seen as Not So Tough, @rjfmgy.  It just has to take a longer time and more casualties than expected.  If you don\'t win such a confrontation by the anticipated margin, people start to ask questions.  So if I were they, which we have established I\'m not, I\'d not bother with an assault on the embassy for rather a while yet.  The embassy is  already a bauble and not a jewel in anybody\'s crown.  Nobody wants to overpay for a trinket.  (Well, the cruise ship turistas from New Jersey standing around in short pants buying baskets do, but most of them are not Taliban.)','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1309670'),(2,'rjfmgy','2021-07-19 16:56:00','@cdob63, All true enough, but the embassy doesn\'t have to be attacked for the question to close as a \"Yes;\" just the threat of Taliban control of Kabul  might be enough to provoke an evacuation.\nIn a way, there are too many variables to speculate (at this stage) on which specific circumstances might close the question as a \"Yes.\"','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1309830'),(2,'dowser','2021-07-19 17