erage in Germany, in some places like Hessia with much international travel (FRA airport) it already exceeds 20%.\nIt\'s roughly doubling every week, so we might observe a 50% to 60% share two weeks from now, when decision makers will ultimately be confronted with the question of giving the opening a go.\nNew confirmed infections have dropped to 1,000 per day across Germany, but I suspect this will be the lowest it can get for a while, and infection rates will be surging again amid all the simultaneous opening and the effect the UEFA Euro 2020 (teams travelling AND spectators in the arenas and at home) will have on the pandemic.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1297548'),(4,'Columbus','2021-06-02 17:03:00','@DNK89 In this article there is a summary of the latest information. In a May 25 press release, the Humboldt Forum wrote that it can open despite technical problems. They say that the building has long been approved for construction. If that is not the case, they would not be allowed to open the outdoor area next week and plan a partial opening for mid-July.\nHowever, there is a lot of stress behind the scenes. IT security doesn\'t seem to be in place and the mood among employees is abysmal. So it may well be that pressure is being built up on the management through various channels, including the public. From my German point of view, the partial opening can only be stopped if the building inspectorate comes to new findings and demands improvements, which after all is very unlikely and would be a major scandal.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1285827'),(4,'DNK89','2021-06-03 07:30:00','As you say, there is nothing new in the article (turns out even the employee issues were known before the May 25 announcement) and just a summary of already existing issues. Thanks for the point of view. Increasing my odds for a `Yes`. There has been no noticeable pushback from the government and that i guess can be construed as a positive.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1286