lestone will become due and is missed with fanfare? Thus, was the whole announcement of the opening plans for July just based on HOPE everything will be fine before the next milestone will be due (this is what reminds me of the BER scandal most...)\nI forecast 99%, but mainly because I\'ve been most aggressively forecasting \"No\" before.\nOn the smallest harbinger reports that critical timelines with trouble shooting will not be met (which seem to be inevitable, frankly), I\'m prepared to forecast 0% again.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1282435'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-05-26 08:51:00','\"Darin teile er dem für die Ausführung zuständigen Bundesamt für Bauwesen und Raumordnung mit, die Mängel machten einen \"geregelten Betrieb unmöglich und gefährden das bereits eingebrachte Kulturgut\". Auch eine übergreifende Sicherheitsarchitektur für die IT-Infrastruktur werde vermisst.\"\nhttps://www.rbb24.de/kultur/beitrag/2021/05/humboldt-forum-baumaengel-eroeffnung-juli-.html\nhttps://www.sueddeutsche.de/kultur/humboldt-forum-berlin-sicherheitsmaengel-museen-1.5303217\nIn very uncertain what is true now... :-)\n(From the first cancellation of a scheduled opening the BER Airport to the public due to technical deficits (scheduled for June 2012) until the final opening (November 2020) it took more than 8 years...\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flughafen_Berlin_Brandenburg#Bauskandal )','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1282405'),(4,'Columbus','2021-05-24 21:02:00','@keith-huggins It was never planned to open the Humboldt-forum completely, it was always to be done in partial steps. So a partial opening would meet the criteria - in my opinion','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1281405'),(4,'keith-huggins','2021-05-25 07:13:00','@Columbus I would agree with your view, but the Museum appears to be partially open now and the question is still open and remains unresolved. Is the intention therefore, that the question refers to a full opening, which is a point I was making?\nhttps://www.archpaper.com/2021/04/the-humboldt-forum-in-berlin-is-finally-open-but-it-fails-to-inspire/ \nhttps://www.european-traveler.com/germany/2021-berlin-state-museums-opening-hours/','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1281575'),(4,'Columbus','2021-05-25 07:22:00','@keith-huggins Most museums are open, but the Humboldt Forum is not yet, so the question is still open. The Humboldt Forum, because it is new, was very political and very expensive, has to get its own opening date. But as I said before, it will only be a partial opening, because it was always planned that way. A friend of mine is a curator there and she explained it to me that way, which is also official.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1281577'),(4,'LokiOdinevich','2021-05-17 23:03:00','\"Öffentliche Veranstaltungen in geschlossenen Räumen dürfen bis zum Ablauf des 13. Juni 2021 mit nicht mehr als 20 Personen stattfinden. Bei Veranstaltungen mit mehr als 5 Personen müssen alle Beteiligten einen aktuellen negativen Corona-Test, einen vollständigen Impfnachweis oder einen Genesenennachweis vorlegen.\"\nSo, not happening until the 13th of June. Unclear how this affects the rest of the period','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1278494'),(4,'Columbus','2021-04-23 21:15:00','@SE_Meyer If the \"emergency brake\" really works, which of course nobody knows, shouldn\'t normal life start again afterwards?  Isn\'t that the real goal of the \"emergency brake\"? Consequently, the Berlin museums and the Humboldt Forum should be open again by July at the latest, I think.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1267943'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-24 08:18:00','You\'re correct. I expect the \"emergency brake\" to work.\nAnd it\'s time-limited to 30 June 2021 for the time being. Museums in Berlin in general will be closed until 05 May (?), and the situation will be reviewed then.\nHowever, I also expect the \"emergency brake\" to be extended until 30 September 2021 (probably in June), at least for the sake of having normal conditions under which the general election can be held, and there are voices in the current government (P.Altmaier, BMWi) who advocate \"no privileges\" for the vaccinated. Under these conditions, it is hard to see a sensible opening date \"to the general public\", which would be fair and not discriminate at least a group of younger citizens.\nFirst 100 days will come with no entrance fees, so it does matter when this period starts, in order to be part of it. The organizers of the exhibitions also cannot be interested in the Humboldt Forum being stormed by visitors in the last few days of such a period, just because most of them have not had an ooportunity to visit before. \nOne of the exhibitions, \"Berlin Global\" of the Berlin city museum, is planned to expire on 31 August 2021, but I guess in case of a belated opening, this exhibition will just be extended.\nBerlin will also always have an incidence rate slightly above national average from now on, and thus will be one of the states where normalcy returns last.\nThe only reason I currently see that enforces an opening rather sooner than later would be the city\'s economic senate will not want to forego a complete summer tourist season 2021, but at the same time, this sort-sighted approach has brought Germany into the situation it is in now. The ICU capacity at Charité will be crowded for a long time into the year, and thus to me the most reasonable approach would be to have an opening to the general public in September or Q4, at a time when vaccination will have been possible for everybody.\nHowever, there are currently a few job openings at the Humboldt Forum, which is a sign of ongoing planning. But most of the \"operational\" positions (security, serve staff,...) come with an indefinite start date \"until further notice\".\nThere has been so much \"muddling-through\" in the past few months (which didn\'t work well, and people are fed up with), I guess the Humboldt Forum will not want to stain their first year with more of \"muddling through\", and will chose a later date for the sake of clarity and accessiblity.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268086'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-24 11:21:00','Currently 23 million vaccinated. 83 million total population. Herd immunity is 80%. Let\'s call it 40 million. That\'s roughly 13 weeks, or the length of this question. And you think cultural institutions aren\'t going to open before full herd immunity is reached, given they almost opened in March? Well, we\'ll see.\nGerman health minister Jens Spahn said the country was heading towards giving 3.5 million vaccinations a week by the start of May, aiming to cover the population by the end of summer.\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/society/2021/apr/10/france-and-germanys-covid-vaccination-programmes-pick-up-speed','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268109'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-24 11:44:00','@cafebedouin \nThe \"game\" has been changed frequently over the past 14 months, and it could happen once more.\nhttps://www.zdf.de/nachrichten/politik/corona-indische-mutante-evp-100.html\nExperts have long expected mutations to occur, but some are also surprised how many of them have grown significantly at this early stage, and how fast they travel the world.\nWould you, as a polititian, with a respiratory disease that by and large transmits indoors over aerosols (which is now almost common sense) risk the success of a nationwide vaccination campaign for a few nice hours for a few at a museum? I wouldn\'t.\nAgain this is still a \"solidarity\" issue. If they scale up \"normalcy\" for the happy few fully vaccinated (that may grow to 50% by August 1st) too fast, and cause further damages (budgets being overburdened by new debt is also considered a damage in Germany - not in the U.S., maybe), there will be a growing sense of moral failure and maybe even a revolt among those who continue to be locked in. There\'s a growing sense reflected in polls that Germans prefer tough restriction until it\'s over, to have it over more quickly. Joyful moments in arts & history don\'t really fit into this equation, when there are digital alternatives in place. And the logistics under tough German data protection laws are a serious issue, too. The most prominent tracking app is now accused of neglect at data protection, and the development of a national government-funded app with full functionality is slow, I wonder if it will ever work properly.\nhttps://www.luca-app.de/\nhttps://taz.de/Versagen-der-gehypten-Corona-App/!5759224/\nhttps://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/corona-warn-app\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corona-Warn-App\nhttps://www.zdf.de/nachrichten/politik/corona-warn-app-neue-funktion-100.html\nFurthermore, in a trade-off between museums and keeping schools open and enable pupils achieving a degree, I think the choice will be unambiguous.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268111'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-24 14:25:00','No need to argue the point. We need only wait. Even the crowd is 58% on this question.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268149'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-24 16:16:00','I appreciate if you challenge my views.\nBut actually, everyone has to follow his or her own judgment. Mine is different from the consensus, and indeed we\'ll have to wait until mid-June probably for more clues. I closely watch the situation, but I also know Berlin and its peculiarities (I have spent a couple of years there, most of it at a time when the Humboldt Forum used to be not much more than an idea), so I\'m familiar with the situation and the public administration there a bit.\nBy the way, in an interesting coincidence, the  U 5 tube station-project \"Museumsinsel\" in the immediate vincinity will be finalized this summer.\nhttps://www.projekt-u5.de/en/construction-procedure/\nhttps://www.projekt-u5.de/en/museumsinsel/','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268208'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-24 16:31:00','Your argument relies on spread of vaccine resistant mutation, a vaccination rate that is significantly off, e.g., it\'ll be over 25% of the population by end of April and you estimate half by August despite my highlight of the 3.5 million a week number and the final bit, that you have special insight into Berlin politics by dint of having lived there. It\'s a shaky argument all the way around, and not much to discuss really. You may be right, but it doesn\'t look that way from your reasons.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268222'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-24 16:35:00','I don\'t think my insight of Berlin is \"special\", but I guess it helps me understand how people think & behave.\nHave you ever been to Berlin? If no, so what are you talking about, really?\nBy the way, my forecast was like that independent of and prior to the news on B.1.617, but I take this as a confirmation that my concerns are realistic. Just today Jens Spahn confirmed that his ministry categorizes India as a country of origin for mutations (with a different stricter set of rules for travel) in an extraordinary decision, even though the regular, scheduled amendments to the list were made on 23 April already.\nhttps://www.rki.de/DE/Content/InfAZ/N/Neuartiges_Coronavirus/Risikogebiete_neu.html/\nhttps://www.tagesspiegel.de/wissen/ich-werde-euch-alle-mit-corona-anstecken-mann-auf-mallorca-infiziert-22-menschen-und-wird-festgenommen/25560996.html\nPeople in the administration are sometimes asleep at the wheel, but when they wake up their decisions can be heavy-weight.\nI don\'t think it will be the traffic from India that\'s crucial, but the open borders to other EU member states that have already encountered B.1.351, P.1 or now B.1.617, and even the UK. Things could become a lot more difficult in the next six weeks or so, and as long as some 250 citizens are dying per day on average, there\'s no point in relaxing.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268224'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-24 17:08:00','With regards to vaccinations:\nAccording to SPIEGEL ONLINE, currently 5.855mn people are fully vaccinated, 13.110mn people await their second dose. Germany has 82mn inhabitants. There are 14 weeks until 01 August 2021 (however, planning for opening requires maybe two weeks).\nEven if you assume that 2m doses of the 3.5m you mention available per week will be used for second doses, and add 5m doses of Janssen/J&J single dose vaccine, you will hardly arrive at more than 40mn fully vaccinated adults; in 2017 there were about 15mn inhabitants in the age under 20 years (12.5mn 0 through 14 years), and Germany has a significant issue with hesitancy (\"Querdenker\"), so my 50% of adult population-estimate may in the end turn out pretty accurate (unless they start to inocculate first doses only from now on, which I don\'t expect).\nhttps://www.spiegel.de/wissenschaft/medizin/corona-impfungen-so-viele-menschen-wurden-in-deutschland-den-bundeslaendern-und-weltweit-geimpft-a-62f01a1c-f1e0-49d0-b680-818d17252d62','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268239'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-24 17:31:00','Since a single shot provides >80% protection, the focus on full vaccination seems a bit of motivated reasoning, don\'t you think?\nI\'ve been to Berlin, but just visiting. I don\'t think being a resident at some point supports an authority argument in this case.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268247'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-24 17:36:00','Also, coronaviruses aren\'t the flu. They have a lot of mutations in this case since it has infected billions, but a mutation escaping the vaccine is like <5% chance of happening in the next year.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268248'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-24 19:02:00','In order to deal with the pandemic and exclude any new infection caused by a person vaccinated, Germany only considers fully vaccinated individuals - and no earlier than 14 days after their second dose (when full (=as high as possible) protection is assumed). You may like it or not, but that\'s the way considerations are currently made in Germany.\nAnd with these considerations, it is not so much *your* own protection as a fully vaccinated person, but more about the possible infection chain *you* as a fully vaccinated person may start (if \"sterilizing immunity\" is not provided).','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268300'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-24 19:08:00','I don\'t claim any authority, but I have the impression I still know well what\'s going on in the city and in the area, e.g. having worked in nearby Unter den Linden.\nBerlin Marathon organizers e.g. continue to plan for their race being held on 26 September 2021. Their cancellation over the next six weeks may be another sign that things could be more problematic than expected into Fall.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1268305'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-19 18:55:00','Beware of the immune escape variants...\n\"New Variant Under Investigation (VUI) designated\nA new variant has been designated a Variant Under Investigation (VUI) by PHE.\nThe variant, first detected in India, includes a number of mutations including E484Q, L452R, and P681R. [:= B.1.617]\nPHE has identified 77 cases of this variant in the UK and all appropriate public health interventions will be undertaken, including enhanced contact tracing.\nThis variant has been designated VUI-21APR-01. PHE and international partners continue to monitor the situation closely.\"\nhttps://www.gov.uk/government/news/confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-variants-identified-in-uk\nhttps://www.bbc.com/news/uk-56806103','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1265858'),(4,'LunaSol','2021-04-19 21:26:00','I´ll be inoculated by then. I wilI have BioNTech in my body then twice. I´ll wear a mask and be careful. But I will be there unless RKI advises not to be there at all. Be optimistic :-)','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1265974'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-19 21:39:00','I mean with your forecast first and foremost, but it\'s also good to know you\'ll be safe... :-)\nI\'ll try, but not for this question, though ;-)','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1265977'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-06 11:10:00','Spahn talking of \"being vaccinated\" will be treated equally to being tested negative with a fresh test. However, Spahn also said this will make it easier for everyday non-essential shopping and getting your hair cut, no longer having a testing requirement under a testing regime.\nWith museums in Berlin having a trial period with ticketing a certain time frame and a testing requirement, it has proven to bring along very complex logistics.\nAs the whole German response focuses on solidarity (wearing mask to protect others, prioritize the most vulnerable groups for vaccination etc.), the deal is there will be no \"double privileges\" for those already fully vaccinated. The first privilege is being vaccinated first, while others still wait and hold out due to scarce vaccines. The second privilege would be being able to return to \"normal life\" based on one\'s own vaccination ahead of all others, which is deemed a lack of solidarity.\nIf stringent, German public museums (the Humboldt Forum being one of these) would not open before every single adult has the option of being vaccinated regardless of priority group or age, and thus likely not before mid September 2021. However, there are several high-ranking constitutional law experts in Germany who state that an individual who is vaccinated can no longer justifiably be deprived of basic freedoms granted by the constitution, once it is proven that being vaccinated means one can no longer transmit the virus to others (\"sterilizing immunity\"). However, there are two caveats:\n/even though there are some recent publications that seem to indicate \"sterilizing immunity\" after vaccination exists, I don\'t believe this will have been a final proof yet, and a mutant virus such as P.1 could easily change the balance due to its properties and its ability to re-infect.\nSterilizing immunity as a precondition may never be found without a residual risk.\n/While the governments of Germany (federal) and Berlin (land/city) can no longer prohibit private economic subjects (e.g. a visitor and a privately held museum, a movie theater or similar) from agreeing on and closing a contract about a service, if the infection rate at some point in time is low enough, interventions of the administration into private citizens\' relation among themselves always need to be justified (by the goal of reducing the spread of the virus) and found adequate (being the right measure for achieving that specific goal), any public body as the owner of a museum (the Humboldt Forum\'s ownership is a publicly endowed foundation) can perfectly decide it will not open \"until the pandemic is over\" or \"until everyone is vaccinated\", just to avoid any public discussion or lawsuits against them about  discrimination.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259725'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-06 12:39:00','All you have to do is look at Bundeslinga to think your argument is probably wrong.\nhttps://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54229045','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259741'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-06 12:52:00','Why? The Bundesliga is an outdoor event, although travel to an arena makes it a risk setting. You hardly drink beer and shout in The British Museum as a setting, or in any other museum. And the DFL (Deutsche Fussball Liga e.V., a private enterprise organized as an association) is not a public museum. Why should my argument be wrong?\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die_Liga_%E2%80%93_Fu%C3%9Fballverband','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259746'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-06 13:04:00','By the way, the article you cite suggests to me that the Bundesliga having home fans allowed back in may not be totally coincidence: \nhttps://qlur.com/news/722793/uefas-due-date-for-euro-2020-hosts-as-well-as-wembleys-fan-strategies#\nThere have long been rumors that the 2020 UEFA European Cup, planned for different host cities acoss Europe, could be relocated to Germany in a last attempt to save the tournament from cancellation.\nFans being allowed into arenas in some places in Germany now, could simply  be the test case for those potential host cities strict hygiene concepts and feasibility test.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259749'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-06 14:30:00','It\'s obviously wrong. Your whole argument rests of the solidarity premise, and there\'s going to be a natural push for people that are vaccinated to get back to \"normal\" life. It\'s already happening here in the U.S. with vaccination rates at merely 1/3 of the population. And \"normal life\" includes museums. If people can go to movie theaters, people can go to museums.\nhttps://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/coronavirus-germanys-biggest-state-open-cinemas-may-30-1293076','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259787'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-06 15:44:00','Actually, the solidarity premise is not my idea, but the premise the federal German government has followed for 14 months now, and I guess it won\'t change substantially until the end.\nhttps://www.zusammengegencorona.de/\nhttps://www.google.de/search?q=corona+solidarität\nhttps://www.deutschlandfunkkultur.de/solidaritaet-in-corona-zeiten-niemand-ist-sicher-solange.990.de.html?dram:article_id=492042\nhttps://www.gesundheitsforschung-bmbf.de/de/solidaritat-ein-gebot-der-stunde-in-corona-zeiten-12794.php\nhttps://ec.europa.eu/info/live-work-travel-eu/coronavirus-response/coronavirus-european-solidarity-action_de\nAs I mention, in Germany there\'s a distinct difference between private only business (and museums) on the one hand, and public entities on the other hand.\nhttps://www.spiegel.de/gesundheit/diagnose/corona-ethikrat-spricht-sich-gegen-sonderrechte-fuer-geimpfte-aus-a-d63769d2-6250-4642-8f08-05ecfb486ad8\nhttps://vcdn01.spiegel.de/players/b2mlJ4mQ-9QTGcSm3.html\nhttps://www.ethikrat.org/en/publications/publication-details/?tx_wwt3shop_detail[product]=150&tx_wwt3shop_detail[action]=index&tx_wwt3shop_detail[controller]=Products&cookieLevel=not-set','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259816'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-06 15:54:00','Do you think movie theaters will open in the time period?','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259821'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-06 18:35:00','I\'m not sure it would be a bright idea -  but that wont keep some people from trying...\nAll the largest \"open air\" music festivals in Germany have been cancelled for the second year in a row\nhttps://www.hurricane.de/\nhttps://www.southside.de/\nhttps://www.rock-am-ring.com/\nhttps://www.rock-im-park.com/\nhttps://www.deichbrand.de\nMost of them are affiliates to the same large booking agency, but as far as I know there\'s only one festival that intends to try it with hygiene/testing concept in 2021.\nhttps://www.fusion-festival.de/de/x/home','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259912'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-06 18:57:00','Doesn\'t matter if it is smart. The question is whether it will happen. Movie theaters will either need government support or they will need to open. Same with many venues, including museums. So, in the face of declining cases, what will the government do? You don\'t have to guess, look at the history.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259924'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-07 02:25:00','What does matter, is that the Humboldt Forum is not a privately held movie theater.\nJust recently, they received 10mn EUR extra financing for pandemic related to delays just between November 2020 and February 2021.\nIn total, 30mn EUR cost on top of 644mn EUR amount for delays related to construction since the pandemic began:\nhttps://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/humboldt-forum-wird-immer-teurer-baukosten-fuer-berliner-schloss-knacken-680-millionen-grenze/26951796.html\nEven though private donations are involved, too, they make up a minuscule share of total cost. I guess nobody expects them to operate at a surplus in the first year. So any deficit will ultimately be come up for by Mrs. Gruetters indefinite cheque book.\nYou would not compare AMC Holding to the Library of Congress, would you?\nWhat comes close to the Humboldt Forum, both with respect to the structure as a public private partnership and the total cost of construction, is the Elbphilharmonie in the city of Hamburg\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elbphilharmonie\nThe main difference seems to be that the construction part of the Humboldt Forum is ready now on schedule, and has been slightly less chaotic in total.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260082'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-04-07 05:00:00','All you have to do is do a search in Google news. Berlin was going to open cultural venues on March 16, when there were a 150,000 active COVID-19 cases. What do you think is going to happen when it drops back down to a fifth of that? No need to guess, museums in the United States are opening now too, with 7 million active coronavirus cases. You think there\'s not going to be some access in the next 4 months? Well, maybe. But, I don\'t buy it.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260126'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-07 06:31:00','\"Berlin was going to open cultural venues on March 16,...\" that\'s true, but that planning was made on the baseless assumption the pandemic will be under control after the December tightening of restriction. The emphasis lies on the word\"was\". This obviously did not work.\nI agree, there are certainly very tangible plans for an opening rather sooner than later in the second quarter, but you simply neglect at least three important factors:\n/there\'s not one decision-making body only, but as much as six stakeholders which are involved in the Humboldt Forum\nIf only one important stakeholder, such as the city of Berlin\'s public health management will veto in a regular consultation, the opening will not happen.\n/the Humboldt Forum is a newly built museum\nWhile other museums had already opened and will now close again, and can simply reactivate staff, security and all other operational planning once there\'s a credible option for a next phase of relaxation, the Humboldt Forum is still in the phase of initial recruiting and turning plans into reality for the first time, so whenever they are forced to halt operations, they are starting from the scratch next time, which makes them less flexible and the whole process a lot slower. Opening in the case of the Humbold Forum not only means printing posters for the upcoming exhibitions with a corrected date. With a cyclical emergence of a bad pandemic situation (Berlin now has less than 10% of spare ICU beds and Germany is not even near the peak of a third wave, and Berlin hospitals are the centralized healthcare provider for the entire region), planning for the Humboldt forum in the past tended to be near execution whenever case numbers turned too bad to be realized, due to lead time.\n/there is a discussion about \"centralization\" of the handling of the pandemic, which would lay more responsibilities into the hands of the central federal government, since the past waves proved that state governments did not stick to critical policy measures agreed to in the federal/state framework, for their own local political calculus. With the 2021 German federal election nearing,\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_German_federal_election\nthe federal government simply cannot afford to have a fourth, fifth and sixth wave, and thus the dominant election campaigning strategy appears to be:\n(i) impose tough measures now (just as the public opinion welcomes) and put all the necessary atrocities into the second quarter of 2021 and (ii) release the electorate from the pain just in time before the election (maybe in August) in a lot better shape and situation with only a few hundred cases per day. Experts, medical advisors and leading doctors have long advocated such an approach but sadly their voices fell on deaf ears so far. Now there\'s some sort of panic unfolding in the federal government, and a horror scenario of peaking at 100,000 cases per day and triage in hospitals and a total of 200,000 deaths (currently at 75k) is seen as the worst outcome of being too timid. The federal government is a major stakeholder in the Humboldt Forum.\nYou don\'t have to buy it, but good luck with your decision. The next info from the city of Berlin about how to proceed will likely be published today.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260150'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-06-14 19:07:00','@SE_Meyer: how\'s this one looking to you these days?','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292016'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-06-14 19:14:00','Have they opened anything yet except from the cafe and the gift shop? Not that I know of...','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292023'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-06-14 19:17:00','Pretty much the reply I expected. Thanks.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292024'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-06-14 19:32:00','Actually it was a question of mine.\nBut here\'s another one: How long do you think it will take Germany to find itself in the same spot as the UK, which is between a rock and a hard place?\nhttps://www.politico.eu/article/uk-lockdown-end-delayed-freedom-day-june-21/\nLiberal politicians now openly discuss to abandon mask mandates even indoors (even though it\'s just sabre rattling in their election campaigning...), so my best guess is by mid-July (this year).\nOne should not forget that Germany intends to hold a general election in September, and the Merkel government will try to pass the \"keys to the house in a neat and steady condition\" and holding the election in a safe manner will be one of the major goals.\nThose in charge at the Humboldt Forum would do themselves a favor if they push the opening so it has the chance to become a \"grand opening\", instead of doing it by hook or by crook. But that\'s just my personal view and I\'m not in charge.\nEDIT:\nThe Lancet apparently just published today that the Delta variant doubles the risk for hospitalization.\nWith about 50% of adults vaccinated next month, is it worth it? The major uncertainty will be the weekly results of molecular surveillance and the share the Delta variant will have in about three weeks.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292041'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-06-14 19:51:00','Plan is for mid-July. They have the middle plaza area open.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292051'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-06-14 19:55:00','see\n\"EDIT:\nThe Lancet apparently just published today that the Delta variant doubles the risk for hospitalization.\nWith about 50% of adults vaccinated next month, is it worth it? The major uncertainty will be the weekly results of molecular surveillance and the share the Delta variant will have in about three weeks.\"\nThe middle plaza is a public space. There was little interest in just going there for the view of it among Berliners.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292052'),(4,'Chrisp','2021-06-14 20:12:00','Is it worth it:  yes','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292058'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-06-14 20:35:00','I don\'t have any strong feelings about it. Is it worth it to someone who is fully vaccinated and whose livelihood relies on tourism, hospitality or the service industries? Probably. But, regardless of our opinions on the matter, it\'s going to happen, people being how they are. The only real obstacle to opening in July is if the people running the Humboldt Forum didn\'t use the downtime from the pandemic wisely. I think the chances of that are very low, 1 in 500 territory.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292074'),(4,'cafebedouin','2021-07-20 12:26:00','Done. Movie theaters also open.\nhttps://berlin.premiumkino.de/','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1310201'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-07-20 14:09:00','Nobody cares for the Humboldt Forum today. It\'s pretty tone-deaf and derailed to try to open such a site with dignity when the rest of the nation is either mourning the deaths in the July Flash Flooding or wondering how on earth the multiple warnings of meteorologists could lead to zero reaction with respect to preparedness and evacuation among crisis intervention bodies.\nThe only thing that seems to more or less work in Germany these days is the party preparations in a superfluous museum of Prussian statehood.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1310221'),(4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-04 11:11:00','The Humboldt Forum Fondation, which owns the building and curates exhibitions, writes: \"We will announce an opening date soon – here on our website, via newsletter and on social media.\"\nhttps://www.humboldtforum.org/en/programme-2/ (see \"VISIT\")\nI assume this will be the date the HF will be considered \"open to the public\" (it is also likely vaccinated and/or tested persons will have preferential treatment), and will thus resolve the question. Neither the digital exhibition accessible to the public nor the use of the facility by artists, academics, or other specific groups will influence this date.\nThe Benin bronze controversy has been going on since early 2019 and is in no way correlated to the Humboldt Forum itself, but with the collection of the Museum of Ethnology outside Berlin\'s center in Dahlem, which preserves the colonial heritage of federal museums mainly from Africa (and Asia), and which will move into the new building later this year with all its archives and depots (the interior of the Humboldt forum is a high-tech climatized room for optimal preservation) in an effort to centralize collections and make them more accessible. Identifying \"looted art\" and \"lost/stolen art\" in public German collections has become a more important issue over the past decade, and there are allegations that some museums are hiding looted art on purpose, but in general there are procedures and responsible administrations that systematically analyse origins and provenience of pieces of art and, if a \"lost art\" suspicion is confirmed, hand items back after all. My guess is, if delays happen from now on, they will not be related to the \"Benin bronze\"