countries, though the decisions of those bodies will impact the real \"Deciders\".','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1293853'),(1,'beckersc','2021-06-21 15:26:00','Anneinak, that is a great point, however revenue from broadcasting rights will not come close to covering the cost of the olympics for Japan or the International Olympic Committee (IOC).  First, Japan has official costs of $15.4 billion, but government audits suggest that the actual cost of the olympics could be as much as twice as large. The IOC has agreed to give Japan $6.7 billion for costs, but even with the added revenue (sponsorship, ticket sales), Japan will still lose lots of money.  The IOC is also expected to lose lots of money as well. Revenue from broadcasting rights (which makes up about 75% of the IOC income) is expected to be about $3-4 billion. Overall, totaling all revenue and costs the IOC is expected to lose around $7 billion from these Olympic games. As such, I believe it is relatively clear that these Olympic Games are not helpful economically in the short-run.\nThat being said, as we get closer and closer to the Olympics, many of these costs are becoming sunk costs, and cancelling these olympics will result in both of these entities bearing a majority of the costs without reaping any of the revenue. \nFinally, the Prime Minister Yoshihide Suga will be making the final decision, but with low approval ratings and elections this year, I think that the opinion of the Japanese public will be one of the leading factors in Suga\'s decision.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1295803'),(1,'Anneinak','2021-06-21 18:48:00','@beckersc,\nSuga may be making the decision on behalf of the host country, but it\'s the IOC which decides whether or not to cancel.  If Suga withdraws from the contract/commitment to host, it is my understanding that it incurs financial penalties from the IOC because their contract explicitly says that only the IOC can cancel the games.\nI think that  your point about sunk 