g/explorers/coronavirus-data-explorer?zoomToSelection=true&pickerSort=asc&pickerMetric=location&Metric=Confirmed+deaths&Interval=Cumulative&Relative+to+Population=true&Align+outbreaks=false&country=JPN~USA\nhttps://ourworldindata.org/grapher/excess-mortality-p-scores?country=USA~JPN\nhttps://ourworldindata.org/explorers/coronavirus-data-explorer?zoomToSelection=true&time=2020-03-01..latest&pickerSort=asc&pickerMetric=location&Metric=Confirmed+cases&Interval=7-day+rolling+average&Relative+to+Population=true&Align+outbreaks=false&country=JPN~USA','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1277132'),(1,'erikbays','2021-05-16 06:25:00','I don\'t understand your point. Yes, I understand Japan has a lower death per capita for Covid than the US. What does that have to do with what we are talking about? The Olympics are not being held in the united states, so what does the United States have to do with anything? \nYou could just as easily compare Japan to the Congo or to any other country in Africa. These are places where people are often lucky to get clean water let alone good healthcare, yet they only have a fraction of the covid deaths. This is likely partially because they have a lower median age but also I believe because they are frequent users of Hydroxychloroquine. Africa has about 1% the covid deaths of the US, despite only having 20% the percentage of people over 65. If it was only age, you would expect their death rate to be 20% of the United States.\nhttps://ourworldindata.org/explorers/coronavirus-data-explorer?zoomToSelection=true&pickerSort=asc&pickerMetric=location&Metric=Confirmed+deaths&Interval=Cumulative&Relative+to+Population=true&Align+outbreaks=false&country=COG~JPN\nIf you really wanted to look at the United states, you could compare Florida to California. Florida has been open and not requiring people to wear masks for quite a while and also has one of the oldest populations in the country. They have had Disney world open and have been open for tourists for months. California has one of the youngest populations in the country and has had a very strict lockdowns. You would expect Florida\'s covid rate to be much much higher than California\'s but it hasn\'t been.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1277590'),(1,'Tolga','2021-05-16 11:43:00','My point simply was that the statement \"I find it amusing that the country that is probably the most fanatical about wearing masks is being so hard hit with the virus.\" is wrong, in that they are not being hit \"so hard\". They\'re not being hit anywhere near as hard as a country like the US where a large percentage of the population seem to think their voting habits should impact on their scientific knowledge and basic hygiene and consequently reject masks.\nReally? How good do you think data collection is in the Congo? What is the median age there?\nI don\'t think the differences within the US are as significant as you suggest, and there are plenty of factors that could explain differences between California and Florida, though I\'m not actually sure what truth you are expecting me to draw from their comparison? That if Americans fail across the board to deal with a pandemic then that says something about the success that many other countries have had?','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1277707'),(1,'erikbays','2021-05-16 18:32:00','Maybe you don\'t think Japan has been hard hit, but the Japanese do which is why we are debating this question about whether the Olympics is going to be canceled. The Olympics has never been canceled for anything short of war before, so for this to be a possibility is a pretty major thing.\nI already addressed the issue about the median age in the Congo. It\'s not enough to account for the differences. But your point about data collection is well taken. \nThe idea that people who reject masks have a lack of scientific knowledge is pretty ridiculous. There are more than a dozen randomized control trials that find that wearing N95 masks does nothing to stop the spread of the flu. If it doesn\'t stop the flu, it\'s certainly not going to stop covid-19. To my knowledge there are zero RCTs that find that masks will stop either the flu or covid-19. \nhttps://www.rcreader.com/commentary/masks-dont-work-covid-a-review-of-science-relevant-to-covide-19-social-policy\nIt\'s actually politics that have been pushing masks in the United states, and science that has been trying to tell us that masks don\'t work.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1277897'),(1,'Tolga','2021-05-16 20:19:00','I don\'t think they have been hard hit compared to somewhere like the US where mask-wearing recommendations are flouted, and I don\'t think that\'s wholly coincidental. As for the actual question in discussion, I think that\'s probably going to depend on other factors than just how much coronavirus is in Japan, it will depend on things like the risk assessed as being presented by importation of the Indian variant, for example.\nThe median age in the Congo is 17. In Japan it is 48. 2.7% of the DRC is over the age of 65, 28% of Japan is. The difference in cumulative deaths per capita is only about a factor of 10. I\'m not going to take the time to do a detailed study of it, but it seems very likely to me that the age difference explains the entire difference and then some. The DRC has probably had much more spread of covid. You mention Hydroxycholorquine and take an interest in RCTs, but you should know that use of that is not supported by evidence: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/eclinm/article/PIIS2589-5370(20)30389-8/fulltext\nOn masks: firstly I would ask why you are constraining your interest in masks to N95s, when N99s exist. But to get to your point about studies, it is very difficult to measure the reduction in transmission in terms of number of infections prevented. How would you even design such a study? (If we think most of the effect is in preventing you from infecting others). What we do know is that this virus spreads by droplets and aerosols, and that masks catch droplets and limit the turbulent airflows generating by coughing, in which aerosols and droplets are carried. They likely also have a psychological effect in that they remind people to practice social distancing, and not to touch their face (in fact they present a physical barrier to doing so).\n\"It\'s actually politics that have been pushing masks in the United states, and science that has been trying to tell us that masks don\'t work.\"\nInteresting that things are so different in the United States to the rest of the world... And perhaps it is this perception of masks as a political object that apparently leads you to reject them. \nAlso, you know that it has long since been admitted that the initial recommendations by public health officials (like Fauci, but also in other countries) not to wear masks and that they don\'t work, were lies that were (foolishly, in my opinion) concocted to protect the supply of masks for healthcare workers, right? \nDon\'t know how you guys managed to politicize a pandemic in such a way. I even see that something like half of Republicans don\'t want the vaccine, even despite Trump supporting it, having presided over Operation Warp Speed, and having been vaccinated himself. Truly American political polarization is leading your country to a dangerous place.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1277956'),(1,'erikbays','2021-05-16 23:24:00','\"And perhaps it is this perception of masks as a political object that apparently leads you to reject them.\"\nNo.. actually it is the science that leads me to think the way I do. And I posted links to those RCTs. I notice you didn\'t post any RCTs to support your position. \nAs far as the experimental vaccines, the Japanese are even more skeptical of them than the \"Republicans\" are. And with good reason. We won\'t know if these experimental vaccines have the same problems as the prior coronavirus vaccines that have been tried until phase 3 testing is complete. It hasn\'t even been proven yet that the experimental vaccines reduce transmission. Hopefully they do, and hopefully they pass phase 3 and become approved.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1278027'),(1,'Tolga','2021-05-17 00:53:00','\"No.. actually it is the science that leads me to think the way I do.\"\nWell I would suggest that whatever is leading you is leading you to make an error here.\n\"And I posted links to those RCTs. I notice you didn\'t post any RCTs to support your position.\"\nAnd I supplied you with a perfectly good reason for why I could not supply you with such. I also note that the RCTs you reference only look at an individual\'s ability to become infected, not to spread the disease, which I and others contend is where most of the effect is.\nI\'m not sure of the meaning of \"\"Republicans\"\" here, I only reference polling that appears to show that divide in opinion along political lines. https://www.cbsnews.com/news/vaccine-hesitancy-republican-men/\nBut I think here you may be exposing some anti-scientific credentials (ironically, after brandishing \"the science\"), by treating the vaccines with such a level of skepticism. We are well past phase 3 trials and into phase 4. All the Covid vaccines currently in use in the US have been shown to be both safe and effective against the virus as it is now in America. That may diminish over the course of the next few months as new variants emerge, but you can expect that updated vaccines will be approved in due course.\nAs for Japan, they happen to be a historically anti-vax country, unlike the US: https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-01937-6\nHowever, they are much more approving of Covid vaccines in 2021 than they were of vaccines generally in 2019 (and, as it happens, more approving than Republicans overall): https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2021/03/17/national/vaccine-poll-results/\nAs for whether the vaccines reduce transmission, there is certainly no doubt about this at all: they do reduce it by a significant amount. Any public health officials you might have heard contradicting this are once again telling what they believe to be a white lie because the fact of the matter is there is zero effect until 2 weeks after vaccination, and the effect builds slowly over the course of several months, in the meantime they would like us to continue with social distancing to keep the virus under control, and the best way to manage the public\'s behaviour in such a way is simply to cast doubt over the reduction in transmission. There is also the risk from the new variants, particularly the ones from Brazil, South Africa, and India, and it is very highly likely that the reduction in transmission with respect to these variants is significantly reduced (still, probably not to zero), and this is one of the reasons the vaccines are being updated.\nOut of interest, I am curious which specific problems with prior coronavirus vaccines you are referencing here?','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1278040'),(1,'erikbays','2021-05-17 16:30:00','I understand your mask argument that it is different wearing the mask to prevent transmission rather than wearing the mask to prevent receiving the disease. But just because it may be difficult to set up a RCT going the other direction, that just means it hasn\'t yet been proven. Your theory is still just a hypothesis. \nAs far as information on the previous SARS vaccine that was rejected, I didn\'t have it bookmarked and my search is so far have all been swamped by covid-19 results. If I do find the original source material I will post a link, but I have limited time to devote to that\nPhase 3 trials on the experimental vaccines are NOT complete. They are time-based and take several years. Preliminary results have been released, but don\'t let that confuse you to think that the trials are complete. They have found results that the experimental vaccines reduce symptoms. It is somewhat logical to assume that a reduction of symptoms also means a reduction in transmissibility, however, transmissibility has not yet been proven. \nIf we combine the assumption you seem to be making that masks reduce how much infected people will transmit the virus, and combine that with the assumption that a reduction of symptoms means a reduction of transmissibility, then I guess we could assume that the only people that would ever need to wear masks would be people with symptoms, and they should be isolating themselves anyway.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1278266'),(1,'erikbays','2021-05-17 16:35:00','The RCTs we have involved trained medical personnel who know how to use masks properly, and most of them involved the use of form fitting N95 masks. I find it hard to believe these masks would not have stopped incoming droplets. To think that these trials leave the door open that masks would still be useful the other direction is a stretch to me.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1278267'),(1,'erikbays','2021-05-18 05:22:00','Here you go. One of the bigger concerns seems to be the possibility of the experimental vaccines increasing the chance of ADE. This seems to be what killed the first SARS vaccine in 2005. In animal studies this would typically happen after the animal had the vaccine for a while and was released into the population and then came into contact with the disease.  So the possibility of this particular complication may not reveal itself for some time after people have had the vaccine, and these experimental vaccines have simply not been around long enough to have the long-term testing.\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s41564-020-00789-5\nhttps://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-clinical-and-translational-science/article/potential-for-antibodydependent-enhancement-of-sarscov2-infection-translational-implications-for-vaccine-development/504FE38E2475590EFE93872BC6D67D3D','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1278587'),(1,'Tolga','2021-05-19 13:33:00','\"I understand your mask argument that it is differe