s. The link is directly above. Make sure your team sees that too please. It is the 2nd significant source that verifies the media has accepted Nyima as #21.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1192431'),(3,'LuisEnrique','2020-11-30 03:24:00','@Terry-Smith I can assure you that the crowd consensus has no role in question resolutions. We close questions with the crowd on the wrong side of maybe pretty much every month. And it has been like this since the start. I became a Superforecaster on year 1 of GJP and I can\'t remember a resolution like the one you describe, and I was a very active forecaster on the Russia-Ukraine questions (including one where the crowd was deeply on the wrong side of maybe).\nAs context for others on this thread, @Daveinsea sent multiple resolution requests while this question was open and the available evidence was conflicting, inconclusive, or both. He also sent me several emails over the last week, mostly reiterating the same arguments, which I replied to in detail. A quick count tells me I have personally read more than 46 articles on the events surrounding Tenzin\'s death. I see 48 posts by the team on the resolution of this question on our internal discussion.\nTenzin\'s death hasn\'t been in question since early September. While there were preliminary reports about this death having been caused by a shot in the neck, following reporting stated his death was caused by a landmine while he was on patrol or a reconnaissance mission at the Line of Actual Control. The patrol component comes directly from the Indian Army, per reporting, and the reconnaissance mission at the Line of Actual Control from sources attributed to the Indian Army.\nThere is reporting of yelling matches between Indian and Chinese forces on the day Tenzin died. Also, potentially, of non-lethal maneuvers without any real use of kinetic force (the main article was one which actually Dave found). Crucially, we have the Indian Army explicitly saying his death wasn\'t connected to the only known confrontation/maneuvers that day (https://indianexpress.com/article/india/died-in-landmine-blast-while-patrolling-special-frontier-forces-tibetan-commando-laid-to-rest-6587010/); a confrontation during which available coverage states both Indian and Chinese forces went out of their ways not to cause casualties, and didn\'t.\nIt is also generally indicated that the Indian Army has kept aspects surrounding Tenzin\'s death a secret, at least as it involves a special forces unit.\nTenzin\'s death occurred 2 months after the 20 deaths which closed the first version of this question, making him then the 21st death.\nSo the main thing the team is going to judge is whether the new articles Dave sent present enough evidence to make the confrontation aspect conclusive, in the context of all available evidence (the aforementioned +46 articles). I don\'t know if they will or not. I haven\'t read the new articles yet. As I have been in the weeds of this topic for months, I will ask others from the team to take the first review, trying to get fresh eyes involved. I would just like to assure everyone we take every resolution very seriously and we are as thoroughas we can, taking all presented evidence under consideration.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1192438'),(3,'LuisEnrique','2020-11-30 03:29:00','@Daveinsea let\'s keep resolutions going forward through the usual channels, especially the normal resolution requests. A thread like this can get messy. Trust the process.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1192439'),(3,'Grogu','2020-11-30 04:05:00','Hey @LuisEnrique... that Indian Express article you just posted? That there is no author listed? Just \"Expressweb Desk\"?\nThe guy that wrote the article that got picked up by MSN that claims Nyima was KIA? Praveen Swami? He is the National Editor (Strategic and International Affairs) for the Indian Express. His name is on this one. I think those are important points that shouldn\'t be overlooked either.\nhttps:/