tube.com/watch?v=y-vbPtqkVgQ','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1068837','Upvote\n    (3)',NULL),(674,3,'mthales','2020-06-29 16:37:00',35,'maintaining current forecast','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1068435','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(675,3,'Orao','2020-06-28 22:10:00',25,'The Line of Actual Control has a stark similarity to the Nine Dash Line of the South China Sea.  Discontinuity and disagreed upon.  But there’s also a stark contrast in availability of and location of available resources in each region.|The SCS is plentiful in resources and except for China, accepted universally under the 200 mile UN Convention on the Law of the Sea.  China has ignored the UN and chosen to strong arm the Phillipines, Vietnam and others into resource submission.|The LAC that divides China from India runs through the extremes of mountain and valley terrain, is of interest only to the immediate countries, but abundant in water and a few minerals. A major deposit of zinc/lead was discovered in the disputed Aksai Chin region and mining initiated three years ago by Guanghui Energy.  This area of Aksai Chin is secured by China.\nThe Galwan valley is of military interest in maintaining Aksai Chin security along with river control. \nChina seeks land in the valley and has artificially altered the path of river to create newly occupied Chinese land in the valley.|A patient geographic usurper, the Galwan River activity is now reminiscent of the artificial island buildup in the SCS.  The recent altercation proves tension is high, especially without intervention of the International community.  So a subsequent battle seems inevitable, but more than likely will happen after September 30th.  China as whole needs to maintain a semblance of its eastern relations, or India will further sympathize with Western discontent.|India will continue construction of the DS-DBO road, and China will intermittently chip away at the border, leading to another confrontation.  The plan seems to rely on action surreptitious to the international media and scrutiny, so will go dormant for a time, and will vacillate between each countries macro and micro objectives.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1068063','Upvote\n    (1)',NULL),(676,3,'mthales','2020-06-28 20:30:00',35,'Tweaking down for the moment. Looking for additional information.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067957','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(677,3,'Jason-Jones','2020-06-28 20:03:00',41,'To be honest nobody should take into account my forecast because I barely have enough time to follow this as it is.  But based on my readings so far it seems China has slight upper hand and knows it.  It seems China may not be willing to back down, which puts India in a difficult spot.  That\'s my read for now. Hopefully I can find some signal in the noise I can latch onto to increase my confidence one way or another.  I think the crowd is mostly correct here in that the chances are less than 50%.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067950','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(678,3,'juancambeiro','2020-06-28 19:29:00',52,'Great read: https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/06/26/galwan-border-china-india-war-conflict/','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067943','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(680,3,'blackswan202','2020-06-28 15:09:00',24,'they are under international scrutiny and would not like to escalte the situation','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067662','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(681,3,'JChr','2020-06-28 14:42:00',68,'Lowering my forecast by 20%, since there was no immediate retaliation by either side. However, I think an accidental clash rather than an intentional one is more likely, with more troops in the area and relative independence of high ranking Chinese officers.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067625','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(682,3,'LokiOdinevich','2020-06-28 10:29:00',40,'Factors close to the situation:\n- Does the leadership of each of the two countries want a conflict to erupt? Unclear; the Indian PM seems boisterous. (https://eoivienna.gov.in/?pdf10596?000) +20%\n- Is the leadership willing to give operational independence to its ground troops? Probably? +5%\n- Would those ground troops use that independence wisely? Probably not.  +10%\n- **Did India stop its infrastructure construction?** Unknown; made a query. +0%\n- How much weight do I give to the de-escalation talks? Unclear. -20%\n- Both nations seem to be increasing their forces in the region: https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/06/27/world/asia/ap-as-india-china-border-standoff.html +10%\n- Is the situation anti-inductive? I.e., do more skirmishes lead to less skirmishes, or to more skirmishes? What direction do the feedback loops point to? Unknown, can go either way? But it seems to me that the situation, if left alone, leads to more skirmishes, rather than less. +10%\nTotal: 25%|Factors outside of the situation:\n- How much of a black-box is this question for me? Yeah. I was wrong in the previous question. -> Closer to 50%, so +10%\n- What is the appropriate prior here? If in the last 12/30 days there has been one skirmish, what is the probabily there will be another one in the next three months? The naïve prior (1/12 or 1/30 probability per day) outputs really high probabilities. Playing outside-view pingpong leads me to think that a natural starting point is the beginning of June.  -> Closer to 100%, maybe +10%\n- Information filtered by sensationalism: Alarming news is more eye-catching, so I\'m likely to have encountered it more. -10%\nTotal: 35%|Besides all the highbrow media which the commentariat is sure to have consulted, the Sun happens to have a short, & sweet overview with plenty of pictures: https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/11884603/china-war-india-border-nuclear-run-away/ The pictures are surely selected to generate strong emotions on the reader, but they still produce a +5%|Total: 40%.|Will adjust with the passage of time, and other news.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067522','Upvote\n    (3)',NULL),(683,3,'DelapsusAngelus','2020-06-27 16:50:00',38,'Increase in activity = increased likelihood.|https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/06/27/world/asia/ap-as-india-china-border-standoff.html','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067144','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(684,3,'fisherdbus','2020-06-27 16:48:00',54,'Upping for awhile. A lot of military hardware in that area. Waiting to see if tension resides. It hasn’t.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067141','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(685,3,'osbad4','2020-06-27 16:33:00',24,'While I would generally have said that no conflict in the first week was a good sign of deescalation with the largest risk being while tempers flare, there are a lot of stories of build up of troops on both sides of the border. Raising my prediction slightly due to that, outweighing the decrease of no violence in first week.|https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/06/27/world/asia/ap-as-india-china-border-standoff.html','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1067132','Upvote\n    (1)',NULL),(686,3,'Rpetroff','2020-06-27 02:35:00',20,'Though China would like to use global chaos to make some bold moves, they are cautious enough to put their domestic issues and dealing with the rising Chinese cases of Covid-19 first.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066793','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(687,3,'Dogopotamus','2020-06-27 01:54:00',48,'Straight-lining down over the next 13 weeks.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066780','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(688,3,'Indiresha-Ramachandra','2020-06-27 00:38:00',70,'Some talks have occurred. However, troop buildup and structures being constructed can make a lethal confrontation possible','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066752','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(689,3,'username-deleted 90732','2020-06-26 23:04:00',35,'Lowering my initial projection. India is overly dependent on China for trade, China is also militarily superior. Cooler heads will prevail.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066700','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(690,3,'Michigan','2020-06-26 22:45:00',3,'Major General level daily talks resumed, after the casualty rate of 20 soliders both sides will be quite cautious over next few months so as to not esclate the issue any further. Anything beyond that will put india in a position where it may have to react and that can put china in a very difficult position','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066673','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(691,3,'fisherdbus','2020-06-26 21:29:00',42,'They gave both beefed up their military in the area. https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/06/india-china-deployed-army-large-numbers-disputed-border-200626031842005.htm\nhttps://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/government-warns-china-of-consequences/articleshow/76633922.cms|https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-53174887','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066630','Upvote\n    (1)',NULL),(692,3,'DelapsusAngelus','2020-06-26 16:54:00',33,'My initial cold judgement, (I must do more research):|- India must feel pressure to respond from negative (20 dead vs apparently zero the other side) news around this recent fight, therefore some certainty (80-90%) a response will happen;\n- India is impacted by COVID-19 quite substantially and ability to recover must be the higher internal concern - will this be resolved prior to 30 Sep 2020, unlikely at present;\n- China must therefore sense opportunity to seek advantage, although I feel this is more likely by taking territory or increasing infrastructure;\n- India less so (from a military response rather than building infrastructure), however, Chinese PR is at quite a low from larger international community, Aus, UK, US etc.\n- India would then likely over-compensate immediately if China physically escalated twice (as the Indian\'s see it) with back-to-back instances;\n- Increase in activity from both sides makes a situation more likely than unlikely to occur;\n- Could both sides benefit from this publicity as opposed to other on-going internal and external (less external for India) issues;\n- I found it interesting that during this fight, no firearms were used as agreed within a treaty - even in a life and death scenario no ammunition was used beyond basic tools. Some control is there.\n- India must still consider 1962 dispute as found in NYT article since China has expanded it\'s military capability significantly since this date, India somewhat in comparison:(https://www.nytimes.com/2020/06/19/opinion/China-India-conflict.html). Quote \'the border dispute flared into a war. China won conclusively\'.\n- Method of attack is interesting (from same article): India protested. On June 6, Indian and Chinese military officers started talks to de-escalate the crisis. The Chinese agreed to vacate some positions. On the evening of June 15, an Indian Army patrol set out to verify whether the Chinese had withdrawn from positions on the Indian side of the Line of Actual Control.|According to the Indian officials, the Chinese had not withdrawn as agreed, and several hundred Chinese soldiers ambushed the Indian patrol. The Chinese claim they were on their own side of the Line of Actual Control when the Indian soldiers crossed over and attacked them.|While both Indian and Chinese soldiers carry weapons when they patrol the border, it has been a longstanding practice, in accordance with agreements signed by the two countries in 1996 and 2005, not to use firearms during patrol clashes. Brutal hand-to-hand fighting followed in which the Chinese killed at least 20 Indian soldiers , pushing some of the wounded over the steep cliffs overlooking the Galwan River.|- Conclusion:\nAt present, I am thinking between now and 30 Sep, both sides will aggressively build infrastructure. India will be keen to expand territory which may increase likelihood of retaliation/ further confrontation as time goes on.|Side note: I must admit that the inclusion of militia in the question does make it more probable for a response from India, however, I have concluded with the increased military numbers in the area who will be keen to control any non-governmental retaliation and with COVID-19 worries, it will be difficult for any militia to insert itself, despite their probable need for \'revenge\'.|Please critique.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066417','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(693,3,'JRajanayagam','2020-06-26 13:40:00',70,'The Chinese intrusion into the Indian territory in June 2020 has put the ball in India\'s court and India is in a situation to respond to this. If it does not, China will have achieved its strategic objective. If India does, whether it gains or loses in a limited conflict, it will show to the world its capability. \nIndia has, in the recent past, shown its capability and its ambition and its position that it will not surrender. \nHence, the chances of a limited conflict are high.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066313','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(694,3,'robertpage','2020-06-26 12:36:00',30,'After the lethal confrontation both sides will seek to deescalate, however an accidental clash is possible','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066289','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(695,3,'DippySkippy','2020-06-26 01:59:00',15,'Feel initial shock has passed, next four weeks crucial in regards to the question. Think historical precedent means can say quick repeat unlikely, additional problem is that I can\'t see the Chinese verifying any losses from their side.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066080','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(696,3,'jpalasma','2020-06-26 00:45:00',98,'I know I\'m an outlier, but I am increasing!  China has brought in 10,000 troops along the border, including tanks.  They are working on infrastructure to support their troops there.  They\'ve rebuilt the tent facility that was the initial cause of the dispute, even while they were having military talks with India.  Meanwhile, India tried to cool tensions for a moment while they were \"talking\" but have meanwhile brought reinforcements in as well, and finished the road and bridge they were working on (which was got China riled up in the first place).|Let\'s just assume that India has the cooler heads, and they let this go.  China has ALSO brought troops in near Pangong Lake, and if China gets away with it at Galwan, why not try there as well?  China would love to have a little nationalistic news to divert attention from covid and the economy.|I don\'t believe for a second that the military talks of peace were anything buy buying time, so both sides could supply up.  India wants to maintain as much control as they can keep in the Kashmir region, and China wants as much control as it can get in the entire region.  From a personal standpoint, I spent time trekking in the Himalayas in Nepal around 2000, and news of China trying to seize control of the area was constant.  20 years has passed, and I can\'t see that anything has changed.  I think China will take advantage of the rest of the world (and India!) being focused on covid to see what they can get away with in this region.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066061','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(697,3,'sclare','2020-06-25 23:57:00',25,'Considerations here:\n-Lethal confrontation rare on longer timescale (1 in 50 years)\n-Galwan Valley result of rising tensions, prolonged military buildup that has not been deescalated\n-Recent talks resulted in statements pointing at some level of agreement, different than previous failed talks\n-Physical confrontations common, but not necessarily lethal ones\n-No further incidents in 10 days since Galwan\n-3 months until question resolution\n-I don\'t think either country benefits from more lethal confrontation right now|Although I don\'t expect a good resolution to this dispute anytime soon, the low base rate of lethal confrontation and signs pointing to some deescalation since Galwan make me think the chance of a lethal conflict is lower than it was 2 weeks ago. I think I\'m at about 20% now, bumping it up a bit to account for uncertainty in the next 3 months.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066052','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(698,3,'Ruminandum','2020-06-25 13:05:00',30,'- Tensions generally perceived to be easing, e.g. https://www.nwaonline.com/news/2020/jun/24/china-india-to-disengage-forces/\n- Detrimental economic impact for India, if it were to pursue a conflict with China, (esp. in coming months.) Data appears to re-enforce this, e.g. https://www.thehindu.com/data/data-is-an-economic-boycott-of-china-feasible-for-india/article31903776.ece|- One might say, \"The air has already been let out of the balloon now...\"','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1065620','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(699,3,'Suzukisamurai','2020-06-25 05:19:00',27,'The recent conflict could of broken the ice','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1065466','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(700,3,'Censusguyz','2020-06-24 19:16:00',55,'I\'ve polled and discussed the events sop far with learned men, men who have been there and military experts. The Consensus? China had been looking for a pre-text to create an unsolvable problem, for purposes of diversion of attention and intel assets while they do something else. What is it? Covid I\'m sure. My Point - this isn\'t driven by military principles or initiatives of state - so they will heat up and cool off as suits the needs of the Chinese.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1065124','Upvote\n    (1)',NULL),(701,3,'bobrown','2020-06-24 15:59:00',5,'Dramatically downshifting as situation appears to have stabilized to \"normal\'.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064928','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(702,3,'eshriver','2020-06-24 15:31:00',3,'Interesting article today from Statista on India\'s (current) response about boycott as their response to the most recent clash, in spite of the fact that India is on the weak side of a boycott.  It does suggest that India is at least looking for non military response.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064877','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(703,3,'bbrandreth','2020-06-24 14:15:00',30,'There are continuing tensions in the area that seem unlikely to be resolved, [1], [3].  However, the question now is whether the incident in mid-June 2020 has led the respective commanders to realise how easily a flashpoint could be reached and, accordingly, to pull back from deliberately creating scenarios that might lead to an accidental escalation.  The recent talks suggest that they have - including provision for a demilitarised zone on the Indian side of the border - [2], [4]|The starting point is a low chance of a deliberate confrontation, and lower still that this would result in a lethal outcome.  15 June was an unexpected anomaly.  However, it would be foolish to rule out another such flare up given that the underlying tensions have not been resolved and China is continuing to push aggressively in the region.|[1]https://www.business-standard.com/article/defence/india-china-border-face-off-beijing-talks-peace-amid-troop-build-up-120062302210_1.html\n[2]https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-china-reach-accord-to-diffuse-border-tensions-11592927373\n[3] https://www.business-standard.com/article/defence/india-china-border-face-off-beijing-talks-peace-amid-troop-build-up-120062302210_1.html\n[4]https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-china-border-disengagement-galwan-faceoff-6472274/','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064767','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(704,3,'ROSFAC','2020-06-24 09:54:00',20,'There are lots of countervailing factors increasing/decreasing the likely probability in this one. I found it important to consider the different dimensions of the question as regards actors who could influence the result: state level actors with geopolitical considerations, army generals (+ ministers) with strategic considerations, and individual soldiers.|Overall, I find the probability to be quite a bit lower than the average. Without going fully into the reasons, some of which are mirrored (and stolen from) other forecasters, two observations are: \n(1)Despite Indian troops being given greater autonomy, increasing the chance of an individual incident, I still believe that non-lethal confrontations/stand-offs are possible, as have happened in the past. This gives room for the inevitable conflicts to be solved without lethal consequences. \n(2)Although the escalation of tensions means this period of time bears higher risk than normal, the border conflict is still an ongoing long-term issue and the time quoted in the question is relatively short. Unfortunately for the world, I do believe it is likely the conflict will cause further loss of life, but I think that some of the probabilities quoted (90%+) are not appropriate for a three month period.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064580','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(705,3,'erikbays','2020-06-24 09:19:00',15,'The countries have recently agreed to a de escalation. The recent confrontation was the first fatalities in 45 years so statistically this is rare. Giving is some probability because China has seemed aggressive recently on many fronts, and these are bad economic times. In recessions strong government\'s often turn to war to distract the public and sometimes they even believe it stimulates the economy.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064548','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(706,3,'RosaGen','2020-06-24 08:46:00',43,'[Update]\n[Probability reduced 45->43% in response to news that India/China have reached a provisional agreement on a staged disengagement (https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-china-border-disengagement-galwan-faceoff-6472274/). The risk of local-level miscalculation remains, but this early-stage agreement indicates a mutual willingness to de-escalate.]|Note: Technically this question doesn’t refer to the LAC specifically, so could apply to anywhere. \nUltimately this is a gut feeling estimate rather than a more quantifiable metric. Given that 15 June was the first fatal clash in 45 years there is no reliable statistical soure to base estimates on the number of annual clashes vs the number that escalate to fatalities.|15 June was the first fatal incident between India & China in 45 years. The most recent conflict precipitated by Chinese forces objecting to India road construction in Galwan River valley (undisputed Indian territory, but Chinese don’t like the strategic implications). Fighting on 15/16 June resulted in 20 Indian dead and some Chinese casualties. China claims that “Indian border troops have unilaterally and continuously built roads, bridges and other facilities at the LAC in the Galwan Valley”. China have themselves been pitching tents in a disputed area of the Galwan Valley; this is reportedly part of a Chinese pattern, whereby they pitch tents, then move back after bilateral military-talks, but do not remove or destroy the tents.|Positive modifiers (Strategic):\nChina is raising border issues due to internal problems within China and the international pressure being exerted on China over COVID-19.\nCurrent border tensions have been linked to India\'s decision to abrogate Article 370 and change the status of Jammu and Kashmir in 2019.\nPLA has brought in 6000 extra troops\nIn response to the first incident India has sent 12,000 additional workers to help complete development of infrastructure.\nChina captured 60 km2 of Indian-patrolled territory between May and June 2020. Will India try to regain this?|Positive modifiers (Local):\nIndia has loosened its Rules of Engagement, sanctioning use of firearms in ‘extraordinary’ circumstances. The Indian Army have been given full freedom to deal with on-ground situation.\nIndia has something to prove, ‘blood raised’ on both sides. Any ground interactions between patrols could easily escalate to fatal clashes unintentionally.|Negative modifiers (Strategic):\nChina has (largely) achieved its goal, pushing gaining 60 km2 of Indian territory. A period of consolidation to allow tensions to cool would be strategically sensible.\nNumerous Indian government officials said that border tensions will not impact trade between India and China despite some Indian campaigns about boycotting Chinese products. This appears part of a wider intent within the Indian government to prevent further strategic escalation.|My estimate leans towards no for all of the reasons above, with the primary reasons being due to China having largely achieved their strategic goals, and India largely being unwilling to escalate to a true inter-state conflict. The residual risk therefore (whilst significant) is due to the potential for local escalation between patrols rather than larger scale strategies on either side. This will accordingly be modified as information comes to light regarding troop numbers and other information between now and September.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064532','Upvote\n    (3)',NULL),(707,3,'mthales','2020-06-23 18:29:00',60,'Confrontation likely given history and nature of dispute.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064115','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(708,3,'eshriver','2020-06-23 17:44:00',5,'India is in the throws of another local election, but other than political rhetoric there does not appear any advantage to India.  \nChina has plenty to be focus about too - Hong Kong, constant pandemic outbreaks, a very significant opening up of their economy to the outside world (creating external criticism especially during an American election).  Neither country seems to shows opportunity to gain by a conflict.  There is always a chance a loose nut causes the wheel to fall off, so 5%','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064069','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(709,3,'SE_Meyer','2020-06-23 17:34:00',10,'By now events seem to have slowed down into de-escalation efforts, but in the background, preparations for a full scale war concerning material apparently go on.\nLow forecast for a few days/weeks as long as things are kept calm.|https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/china-says-it-has-agreed-with-india-to-take-steps-to-ease-border-tensions/articleshow/76527189.cms|https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-0