n','2021-06-15 18:26:00',97,'Looks like it will be back open July 20th: https://www.humboldtforum.org/en/programm/termin/opening/finally-open-24469/','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1292598','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(767,4,'SE_Meyer','2021-06-12 17:09:00',67,'The Janssen (J&J) vaccine manufactured at a Emergent Biosolutions plant will fall short of the originally planned amount by 60mn doses  that will not receive clearance by the FDA and will be eliminated from deliveries worldwide.\nThe German Federal Ministry for Health so far expected 10.1mn doses of the single-shot Janssen vaccine in the second quarter of 2021 (April, May, June)), but received only 1.7mn of these doses and only 1.2mn doses have yet been administered.\nIt is unclear whether the Emergent incident will cause a total collapse of deliveries in Q2 2021 and beyond, but it already means that those 8.4mn doses outstanding will have to be replaced by about 17mn doses of any other (two-shot-regimen) vaccine, and potentially delays the federal German vaccination campaign by ONE MONTH on average (Berlin being in the mid field).','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1291005','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(768,4,'SE_Meyer','2021-06-10 20:24:00',82,'Even though the Delta (B.1.617.2) variant is still rare in Germany and accounts for only 2% to 3% of all positive tests under surveillance, it has been steadily growing over the past few weeks and, unlike the Beta (B.1.351) and Gamma (P.1) variants, which have almost disappeared now, is likely to stay and have a growing share.\nGiven its likely higher transmissibility (+60% versus Alpha (B.1.1.7)) and signs of higher likelihood of a severe illness and deadly outcome, and given the initial experience with the Alpha variant in the winter 2020/21, public administrations have raised the alarms somewhat.|It is likely that given the low recent incidence figures (~20/100k population), lots of travel within Germany (mainly North to South, West to North) will spill over the current pockets of Delta/B.1.617.2 which are situated in Northrhine-Westfalia and Bavaria, throughout the country in a matter of week.|UEFA 2020 Euro Championships will bring in additional international travel, even though only Munich (Bavaria) serves as a host city. However, Hessia, with FRA as one of Europe\'s busiest airports, has found an above-average number of Delta, and the pick-up in international travel for summer holidays along with travel to and from sporting events, appear to be a unhealthy cocktail. Delta has even arrived in Berlin and some counties on Berlin\'s fringes and some other East German cities such as Dresden (Saxony). Watching football matches in crowded bars (even if largely outdoors), among neighbors and friends could prove to be prone to fresh outbreaks. In all, it seems set that the share of Delta will follow the pattern of the UK (where Delta has become the \"dominant strain\" already) and increase even in Germany to more than 10% of all cases by end of June.\nGiven the recently slow progress in vaccinations amid repeated scarcity of vials, a \"summer effect\" (reduced viral lifetime of ~20%) that cannot compensate for Delta\'s higher r0 and people partying in the streets like it\'s 2019 and being more careless amid fast reopenings, I\'m increasingly worried that Germany\'s fourth wave of SARS-CoV-2 is going to arrive sooner than expected: Germany may have 10k+ cases per day in July already. With incoming tourist from the EU, Berlin may indeed prove to be at the center of the problem.|A long story cut short, here\'s what the Humboldt Forum organizers say:\n\"Ausblick|Sofern sich die Pandemie-Lage weiterhin stabilisiert, werden im Juli die Ausstellungen im Erdgeschoss und 1. Obergeschoss (Geschichte des Ortes, Einblicke. Die Brüder Humboldt, schrecklich schön. Elefant – Mensch – Elfenbein, Nimm Platz! Eine Ausstellung für Kinder, Nach der Natur und BERLIN GLOBAL) öffnen. Im Spätsommer 2021 folgen der Westflügel der zweiten und dritten Etage mit dem Ethnologischen und Asiatischen Museum sowie die Dachterrasse. In der ersten Jahreshälfte 2022 schließlich steht den Besucher*innen das gesamte Haus offen.\"\nhttps://www.humboldtforum.org/de/besuch-vor-ort/|(No official translation under https://www.humboldtforum.org/en/on-location/ , but it says \"Under the assumption that the pandemic situation continues to stabilize, exhibitions in the basement and on the 2nd floor (Geschichte des Ortes, Einblicke. Die Brüder Humboldt, schrecklich schön. Elefant – Mensch – Elfenbein, Nimm Platz! Eine Ausstellung für Kinder, Nach der Natur und BERLIN GLOBAL) will open in July.\"|My assumption is they are going to use June/July\'s deteriorating situation and the scary outlook for August to postpone the opening into fall (when everybody has been able to get vaccinated and exhibitions (and the city as a whole) will be less crowded by tourists), while the real reason behind may be the mounting pressure from deadlines to trouble-shoot the shortcomings of the building. Their own wording is more cautious and less optimistic than what was purported by the media.|Finally, the strange news about the Humboldt Foundation\'s treatment of staff may make it harder for them to fill vacancies. For example, the foundation is still hiring an \"IT-Enterprise Architekt*in (m/w/d)\" (closing date 25 June 2021, https://www.humboldtforum.org/de/jobs/ ), whose likely task it is to streamline the purportedly fragmented and unsafe software environment which appears to cause a lion share of the trouble within the building (lighting, electricity, dysfunctional doors, box offices, air conditioning,...).\nIf they do find and hire key staff by the end of June, I only wonder just how much a single person can improve a system in a matter of two to four weeks that has been corrupted by dozens of contractors over several months...','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1289981','Upvote\n    (2)',NULL),(769,4,'Eolienne','2021-06-09 19:36:00',55,'https://www.dw.com/en/be