ransfers of ICU patients to other regions in Germany amid continuously high infection rates in some Eastern German counties.|EDIT:\nThe question increasingly boils down to a technical term from German law,\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidemische_Lage_von_nationaler_Tragweite\nwhich is to be declared in case of a pandemic and/or prolonged every three months. The \"state of pandemic emergency\" has been concluded & declared beyond 31 March 2021 lately, and will be running out on 30 June 2021, unless extended once more. I cannot imagine the \"pandemic will be over\" in Germany by the end of June, even with many more vaccinations possible lately.\nThis state, which will likely be extended until 30 September 2021 at least, is the prerequisite for this law\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gesetz_zum_Schutz_der_Bev%C3%B6lkerung_bei_einer_epidemischen_Lage_von_nationaler_Tragweite\nhttps://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/pandemische-lage-verlaengert-1872464\nto be applied, and with said initiative of the federal German government to introduce a more centralized, more automated chain of command for shutting down e.g. museums and other cultural sites, it is very likely there will be no reliable schedule or planning possible for the Humboldt Forum foundation staffing independent of the day-to-day evaluation of local (i.e. Berlin\'s) epidemic data and infection risk. Going by the current state of confusion the German society is in, my best bet is the incidence of cases will remain >150/(7days,100k) for the foreseeable future.\nhttps://www.monopol-magazin.de/mit-der-bundes-notbremse-muessten-museen-und-galerien-schliessen|In order to drive down infection rates significantly ahead of the \"Bundestagswahl 2021\" scheduled for 26 Sep 2021, and thus secure the date and a safe and low-risk opportunity to vote in-person even for people who will not have had the opportunity to get fully vaccinated before that date, the federal government will make lengthy and strict use of its competencies.|https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bundestagswahl_2021','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1264261','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(821,4,'bobrown','2021-04-14 16:34:00',10,'Germany is struggling with policy to limit Covid-19 infections, at this time a no-go. However, there are 60 days where something might happen, e.g. June and July.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1263497','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(822,4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-13 09:23:00',11,'https://www.berlin.de/aktuelles/berlin/6502917-958092-coronaampel-weiter-zweimal-auf-rot-539-n.html|https://www.berlin.de/aktuelles/berlin/6502735-958092-senat-will-lockdown-voraussichtlich-verl.html','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1262815','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(823,4,'derberkerl','2021-04-11 20:22:00',65,'Would have gone up to 80 % likelihood of opening but since outdoor events are excluded i restrict myself to 65 %. It hinges on Covid-19 in particular since the staff already has been hired and trained so in March they definetly planned to open the doors. Its a bet will Germany finally gets it hold on Covid with vaccination etc. For the next 4 week 100 % certainty to be remained closes since a federal lockdown is coming in Germany. Afterwards Germany and Berlin in particular needs some good news and distraction. In July August Septermber since there are federal elections enternainmant wil come back - panem et circensis !!!! They will open i believe.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1262196','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(824,4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-11 11:04:00',13,'This is the most recent press release by Staatliche Museen zu Berlin (SMB) about their to-date plans for further openings, as 13 April.\nhttps://smart.smb.museum/export/downloadPM.php?id=6502|Visitors will be required to wear a N95-equivalent mask at all time, capacity will be limited to 25 people per 1,000sqm (40sqm per visitor), bookings must be made upfront, with an individual, reserved time frame, visitors (even those fully vaccinated) are required to provide a negative PCR-test or rapid test result of the past 24 hours at entrance and will be tracked/personal information will be saved in order to enable health authorities to contact visitors for four weeks after their visit.|The SMB\'s director generale Michael Eissenhauer announced that  in addition to those open since 16 March 2021 \n(Alte Nationalgalerie\nNeues Museum\nPergamonmuseum\nPergamonmuseum. Das Panorama\nMuseum Europäischer Kulturen)|further museums under the SMB tent, will open carefully under the conditions laid out by the Berlin opening strategy (\"Berlin testing\"):\n/\"Kulturforum\": Gemäldegalerie, Kupferstichkabinett, Kunstbibliothek, Sonderausstellungshalle\nMatthäikirchplatz, 10785 Berlin (near Berlin Philharmonic/Potsdamer Platz, not to be confused with \"Humboldt Forum\")\nhttps://www.smb.museum/museen-einrichtungen/kulturforum/museumsgebaeude-sammlungen/ueberblick/|/Hamburger Bahnhof – Museum für Gegenwart – Berlin\nInvalidenstraße 50/51, 10557 Berlin\nnear Berlin central station\nhttps://www.smb.museum/museen-einrichtungen/hamburger-bahnhof/home/|No mentioning Humboldt Forum in this release.\nThe current list of press releases with announcements of planned exhibition starts so far to-date, which includes two known exhibitions after 01 August 2021 already but will be far from complete, does not list any information with regards to Humboldt Forum.\nhttps://www.smb.museum/presse/pressemitteilungen/','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1262014','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(825,4,'noah2k','2021-04-09 11:33:00',15,'There is a very low chance to open when the decision is made by scientists. But there a some less people, who think they can do what they want and because of this I think the probability isn´t down 0.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1261194','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(826,4,'noah2k','2021-04-09 11:32:00',48,'There is a very low chance to open when the decision is made by scientists. But there a some less people, who think they can do what they want and because of this I think the probability isn´t down 0.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1261193','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(827,4,'CUTNPASTE','2021-04-09 10:19:00',0,'81','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1261187','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(828,4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-08 17:59:00',25,'Berlins senate\'s decision of today mostly concerned the opening of schools after the Easter break, which is of high priority.\nhttps://www.berlin.de/sen/bjf/service/presse/pressearchiv-2021/pressemitteilung.1073249.php|All plans for re-opening  as of mid-March footed on the assumption of a further decline in cases per 7 days per 100k inhabitants to well below 50.\nPlans were also based on scientific and technical advice published by the federal German environmental protection agency Umweltbundesamt (UBA), which deems a reopening of theaters, concerts, movie theaters and other rather long-lasting static events at which people are seated to be safe if certain conditions are met AND the above mentioned important threshold of 50 (cases per 7 days per 100k inhabitants) or lower is kept. For cases with a higher actual figure, there is no advice given in the recommendation, since then other aspects and considerations such as the situation the hospitals\' ICUs would be crucial.\nhttps://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/bundesregierung/staatsministerin-fuer-kultur-und-medien/aktuelles/experten-legen-eckpunkte-zur-wiederoeffnung-von-theatern-kinos-und-bibliotheken-vor-kulturstaatsministerin-gruetters-verantwortungsvoller-neustart-ist-moeglich--1872466\nhttps://www.umweltbundesamt.de/sites/default/files/medien/421/dokumente/moriske_et._al._eckpunkte_zur_durchfuehrung_von_kulturveranstaltungen_-_theater_konzerthaeuser_kinos_-_unter_pandemiebedingungen_3.3.2021.pdf\nAlthough museums and libraries are considered slightly less problematic with regards to aerosols due to dynamics/movements in restricted visitors numbers, problems could still arise from crowded situation and groupings of people.|Berlin, similar to Germany as a whole (currently at ~110), has a value of 130 cases per 7 days per 100k inhabitants, and this with the expectation of lower than actual figures due to disruptions in testing and reporting during holidays.\nLast time Germany was in a similar situation at the beginning of the second wave was around 15 October 2020, and it took three months until 15 January 2021 after a peak around Christmas that Germany has reduced the average figure back to the initial level. This time, with more knowledge about Variants of Concern and their potential effect on infection chains, it will likely take even longer to get near the value of 50, which results in mid-July 2021.|Thus what determines the perspectives for openings of museums most will be the situation in high care units of hospitals, for which there exists a nationwide database that delivers an overview about occupied and spare capacities, hosted by the medical association called DIVI e.V.\nhttps://www.divi.de/\nhttps://www.divi.de/register/tagesreport|Two of the most influential voices of the medical community have issued a call for immediate action and for emergency measures in order to prevent hospitals from being overwhelmed in the first week of May.\nProjections show that even under the optimistic scenario for vaccinations the society will likely have to accept a stricter lockdown than ever before, and the longer it takes for decision-makers to come to the same conclusion, the tougher the measures will have to be and the longer it will take until hospitals will return to normal conditions again, on average by 01 July 2021.\nhttps://twitter.com/ECMOKaragianni1/status/1379754846702743553 (head of DIVI e.V.)\nhttps://twitter.com/c_drosten/status/1380058204927885314 (advisor to the federal government)|Even if all things go well and hospitals in Germany experience a mild, managable scenario, a trade-off will remain between inevitable mobility and contacts (schools, essential economic activity) and non-essential sectors such as museums.\nI thus assume that the beginning of holidays could be prove crucial for other sectors to open during summer vacation. For Berlin, this would mean 24 June 2021 as of now, but then again I\'m not sure these dates won\'t be subject to change this year.\nTeachers (about 1mn employees) will have to be fully vaccinated first, before school opening really is more or less safe, and vacations may this year be coordinated with lock downs, but this is rather speculative.\nIn any case and in any scenario, it\'s fairly certain that the education sector will have a higher priority than museums until immunization through the vaccination program nears herd immunity.|EDIT:\nhttps://www.3sat.de/kultur/kulturdoku/countdown-humboldt-forum-100.html','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260883','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(829,4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-08 10:20:00',56,'Four of the stakeholders that curate spaces in the Humboldt Forum (two museums of the public foundation Stiftung Preußischer Kulturbesitz, the land Berlin (Stadtmuseum) and the Humboldt university) currently have consultations about a potential future opening date.\nhttps://www.berlin.de/ausstellungen/nachrichten/6466235-3041403-humboldt-forum-sucht-datum-fuer-echte-er.html|The Berlin senate will have consultations today on further opening, which could follow two different principles:\n/the senate could decide for Berlin separately or \n/the senate could follow a generalized federal approach which effectively means it will postpone a decision until such an approach will be defined by the federal government.\n\"Für Berlin hat Wirtschaftssenatorin Ramona Pop die Debatte eröffnet. Alle müssten „mit der zweiten Impfung ihre vollen Freiheiten leben können“. Am Donnerstag will der Senat darüber beraten.\"\nhttps://www.tagesspiegel.de/gesellschaft/neid-debatte-um-privilegien-freiheiten-fuer-geimpfte-ebnen-den-wartenden-den-weg/27073540.html|However, the federal government seemingly prepares reenforcing the federal infection protection law, which will likely include a wider scope of authority of the federal government.\nhttps://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/corona-angela-merkel-will-bund-durch-infektionsschutzgesetz-mehr-macht-geben-a-4652d0f2-5dc9-479a-a742-0d1cc56e36eb|The discussion about a move towards \"back to normal\" for fully vaccinated Germans focuses on the question, whether there\'s full sterilizing immunity after vaccination, which means immunized people could no longer transmit the virus to others. The Robert-Koch-Institut recently submitted a recommendation to the BMG to regard vaccinated persons as if they have a valid new negative test, which would entail some easing of restrictions. However, this recommendation is not based on proper research but on anecdotical evidence only that suggests that asymptomatic persons are less likely to transmit the virus if vaccinated than with a negative rapid antigen test, and this may prove to be a premature or false conclusion with regards to safety, since this kind of test on average has a false negativity rate of 42%. This would render the whole problem a coin toss.\nhttps://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/inland/rki-corona-ist-auch-nach-impfung-ohne-symptome-uebertragbar-17281800.html','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260685','Upvote\n    (1)',NULL),(830,4,'Emilio-Fich','2021-04-07 21:10:00',93,'Chances are very high, as last year same time the covid incidence rate was low. still there is doubt on the government as with the upcoming legislative ends there might be some power moves to show strength.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260488','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(831,4,'dance1958','2021-04-07 17:20:00',50,'With Covid variants on the rise, I think it may be delayed','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260342','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(832,4,'lenn','2021-04-07 15:47:00',70,'Given the details \"The Humboldt Forum opening to the public with restrictions, such as requiring proof of COVID-19 vaccination or setting occupancy limits, would count.\", I\'m learning towards that it will happen. Either strong restrictions, or vaccination proof.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260307','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(834,4,'2021_cp','2021-04-05 16:04:00',70,'Germany advancing of vaccination is low, but they can ask for COVID test instead of vaccination card. They can open to the public with restrictions.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259423','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(835,4,'Keithle1784','2021-04-05 03:49:00',90,'Technology makes them happy.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259198','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(836,4,'Scappleby','2021-04-04 19:33:00',71,'Cultural institutions are planned to open when the incidence rate is below 50/100k, a week ago it sat at 136, more than doubling in a month, which was cause for increased restrictions until April 18. Roughly 11% have received their first vaccine dose with 40% of those having 2. By July 1 the EU is targeting over 40% of the population being vaccinated, which is likely enough to open the busy tourist season, especially with vaccine passports expected to be in use by mid-June (which again, is to support the tourist season). There will undoubtedly be restrictions on entry but it seems the odds are better than not it will open by August, likely a soft launch in conjunction with the passports in late June.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259099','Upvote\n    (2)',NULL),(837,4,'zzzauberfuchs','2021-04-04 18:34:00',80,'By mid July already there will be most high risk groups be vaccined, also testing for freedom will be a strategy more widely used thus eg it is very likely that all people with fresh test results and people with have been twice vaccined will have free access, general audience with Fsp2 Masks.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1259053','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(839,4,'Captbullett','2021-04-04 10:19:00',0,'Not until 2022','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258954','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(840,4,'bobrown','2021-04-03 16:18:00',0,'Following the excellent explanation offered by @SE_Meyer, and the current state of the pandemic and the lackluster vaccination campaign I\'ll say NO until either of those situations improve.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258685','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(841,4,'AgnesH','2021-04-03 15:55:00',3,'As per @SE_Meyer, https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258493 , there are symbolic reasons to choose a later date.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258680','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(842,4,'Atair','2021-04-03 15:11:00',75,'I assume them opening to vaccinated participants.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258617','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(843,4,'SE_Meyer','2021-04-03 05:46:00',0,'This question is rather complex, like the historic grounds the Humboldt Forum is buildt upon are overly complex, too.|On the surface, the regulation is very easy:\nThe Humboldt Forum is characterized as a \"cosmopolitan forum for culture, art and science\", but first and foremost it is supposed to host the vast collections of several museums in and around Berlin, and a museum with exhibitions of pieces of these collections. It is meant to form an emsemble together with a few more reknowned, important museums on the \"Museumsinsel\" in the historic city center of Berlin: \nAltes Museum (Old Museum), Neues Museum (New Museum), Alte Nationalgalerie (Old National Gallery), Bode Museum, Pergamon Museum and finally the newly reconstruced city castle-shaped Humbolt Forum, which together as a whole \"was added to the UNESCO list of World Heritage Sites\" in 1999. \nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Museum_Island\nThe name, by the way, refers to the Humboldt brothers, who were important advisers to the kings of Prussia in the late 18th and early 19th century and, being researchers themselves, laid the foundation of the Prussian and later German higher education system with a focus on humanism as it is known today.\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_von_Humboldt\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilhelm_von_Humboldt|As a museum located in Berlin (irrespective of ownership or users), disease prevention in Berlin is under the rule of the city (and land) Berlin, which currently states:\n\"Nach ersten Öffnungen Mitte des Monats lassen die Staatliche Museen in Berlin die Türen weiterer Häuser geschlossen.\nZunächst sollen die neuen Regelungen mit obligatorischen Corona-Tests in den bereits geöffneten Museen getestet werden, hieß es am Mittwoch (31. März 2021) zur Begründung. \nErste Museen bereits geöffnet\nIm ersten Schritt waren neben dem Neuen Museum mit der berühmten Nofretete die Alte Nationalgalerie, die James-Simon-Galerie, das Pergamonmuseum und das Panorama auf der Museumsinsel Berlin sowie das Museum Europäischer Kulturen in Dahlem geöffnet worden. Weitere Häuser sollten eigentlich an diesem Donnerstag folgen. Das ist nun ausgesetzt.\nGroßes Interesse an Museumsbesuchen: 30 000 Tickets in zwei Wochen verkauft\nDie bereits geöffneten Museen sollen zunächst bis zum 7. April besucht werden können. Bis dahin werde über weitere Schritte entschieden, sagte ein Sprecher der dpa in Berlin. Das Interesse ist groß. In den zwei Wochen seit Öffnung der ersten Häuser wurden den Angaben zufolge rund 30 000 Tickets verkauft.\"\nhttps://www.berlin.de/ausstellungen/nachrichten/6492485-3041403-staatliche-museen-in-berlin-verschieben-.html\nAmid the infection rates in Germany and in Berlin, the scheduled reopening after 16 March 2021 has been halted on 31 March and re-defined as a \"trial\" for visits to museums and other public spaces under strict testing regimes, which will now end on 07 April for the time being. In general, Berlin\'s \"Infektionsschutzverordnung\" (infection protection act) is due to run out on 18 April 2021, and will likely be renewed and prolonged for four more weeks in a \"Conference of decision makers\" of Bund and laender in the week before 10-17 April 2021, despite some criticism of this format and its outcomes. As a host to the federal government and with its nearly 3.5mn inhabitants, (the city and land) Berlin is of great importance and has a signalling function within the country. It is also a hotspot for international tourism and rather densely populated, so that disease control is a rather difficult task in Berlin, and rules are supposed to be rather strict in the near future.\nFrom this perspective, an opening to the general public is rather unlikely before end of May 2021. For the months of June and July 2021, a seasonal effect could suppress the virus somewhat, so that there will be a permanent pressure in the public opinion for more \"freedoms\", and museums will argue for opening to the public with their budget, the loss in revenue and the fact that alternative routes for infections, such as international travel within the EU, are still allowed.|However, being situated very close to Poland and rather close to Czechia, two countries in which the pandemic is mostly out of control due to mutant viruses, and with respect to frequent work commuting between the countries, mostly into Germany\'s eastern part due to the relatively higher wages, the pandemic and possibly future Variants of Concern (VoC) will be imported to Brandenburg (the land that surrounds Berlin) and Berlin very early and despite all testing efforts at the border. Museums and other cultural sites have a hard time to find a critical argument for why an opening now is \"necessary\", and the Humboldt Forum and e.g. the Louvre in Paris have brought up digital exhibition concepts in order to keep their relevance. In a situation, in which person-to-person contacts and mobility \"in sum\" pose a problem, in-person experience and visits of museum exhibitions are likely on the upper fringe of what the society can abstain from for a while.|There are currently nine exhibitions on schedule for \"Spring 2021\", but this schedule may only be indicative at this point and subject to changes, as the pandemic proceeds, at the moment the Humboldt Forum and all others of the \"Staatliche Museen zu Berlin\" (15 in total) will remain closed after the \"trial\" ends on 07 April for the foreseeable future and \"until further notice\".|Right next to the Humboldt Forum the memorial \"Denkmal für Freiheit und Einheit\" is now under construction, and it already missed the 30th anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall for a scheduled inauguration due to a host of delays and issues. Possible symbolic dates for an inauguration would be 03 October 2021 or 09 November 2021, if construction is to be finished by then. I can imagine that, due to a symbolic value the city castle has as well (from the balcony of the historic city castle, the first German republic, the \"Weimar republic\", and thus democracy, was proclaimed in 1918), there will be a wish by politicians, local and federal, of all parties, to release the Humboldt Forum from the pressure to open to the public soon, and to open both of the sites together and hand them to the public in one large symbolic act on one of the dates in autumn 2021. Everything else could look smallish and inappropriate amid the cost of currently 682mn EUR for the Humboldt Forum alone.\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monument_to_Freedom_and_Unity\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berliner_Schloss|Just yesterday 02 April 2021, the federal government announced plans which will have to be worked out in detail to establish a financial vehicle (\"Kulturfonds\") that will reimburse cultural events (and probably even venues such as museums, imho) for foregone revenues in the future, as there is much talk with respect to the variant B.1.1.7 of a \"totally new pandemic/SARS-CoV-2 as COVID-21\" even by Chancellor Angela Merkel, which is probably an acknowledgement of the fact that the impact of mutants have been widely underestimated as late as in February 2021, when steps of reopening have been decided upon very prematurely. With 2.5bn EUR probably assigned to it, the size is significant and serves as an indication that the cultural life in public spaces will not be what it used to be (and what it is expected to be) in a long long time to come.\nhttps://www.deutschlandfunkkultur.de/2-5-milliarden-fuer-corona-kulturfonds.265.de.html?drn:news_id=1244395|I thus start forecasting \"No.\", but will certainly adapt to new information from the Berlin administration after 07 April 2021.|EDIT: shame on me, for not checking sources first, it appears I mixed up actors and locations in the \"double proclamation of the republic\", a fancy of German history on 09 November 1918. It was actually from a window at the Reichstag (the historic and current house of the German parliament Bundestag) that Phillip Scheidemann proclaimed the \"Weimar republic\" at 2 p.m..\nhttps://www.bundesarchiv.de/DE/Content/Dokumente-zur-Zeitgeschichte/19181109_ausrufung-der-republik.html (an narrative of Scheidemann in person about the historic events)\nhttps://weimar.bundesarchiv.de/WEIMAR/DE/Content/Artikel/Entdecken/scheidemann-rede-film-audio.html (original (?) historic motion picture without tone)\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ausrufung_der_Republik_in_Deutschland|It was actually Karl Liebknecht who held his proclamation speech at the city castle (a legend says \"from within the castle\", a sign the old system of nobility and government of the Hohenzollern family, the emperor\'s family, had been overcome) and proclaimed the \"German sovjet republic\" at 4 p.m. the same day.\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soviet_republic_(system_of_government)\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ausrufung_der_Republik_in_Deutschland#Die_Proklamation_Liebknechts|Being two hours earlier Scheidemann\'s proclamation was superior. However, his republic sadly survived 13 and a half years only.|However, both sites, the Reichstag and the city castle are only half a mile of walk distance apart, and two balcony speeches at the city castle in front of huge masses were used by emperor Wilhelm II to announce Germany\'s preparedness to enter a war in July/August 1914, the first European catastrophe of the 20th century.\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balkonreden','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258493','Upvote\n    (2)',NULL),(844,4,'Ryan-Beck','2021-04-02 22:25:00',75,'Cases are currently rising but I would guess Germany will have most of the population who wants a vaccine vaccinated by late summer and that cases will be much lower than now. I haven\'t done much research at the moment but this seems likely.|Cases in Germany: https://ourworldindata.org/explorers/coronavirus-data-explorer?zoomToSelection=true&time=40..latest&pickerSort=asc&pickerMetric=location&Metric=Confirmed+cases&Interval=7-day+rolling+average&Relative+to+Population=false&Align+outbreaks=false&country=~DEU','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258433','Upvote\n    (0)',NULL),(845,4,'cdob63','2021-04-02 18:46:00',60,'There are 101 numbers available for this answer.  One of them is 60.  Stay tuned for developments.','https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1258359','Upvote\n    (1)',NULL);
